00:01:44,230 --> 00:01:45,856
Quarantine.

10
00:01:46,024 --> 00:01:47,608
You know the cholera?

11
00:01:47,775 --> 00:01:49,318
Yes, Mother.

12
00:01:49,485 --> 00:01:52,404
You've seen the signs on
the houses where the coloreds live?

13
00:01:52,572 --> 00:01:54,239
Yes, Mother.

14
00:01:54,407 --> 00:01:55,699
You know the typhus?

15
00:01:55,867 --> 00:01:57,909
I do, Mother.

16
00:02:00,830 --> 00:02:02,873
You know what they
can do to you?

17
00:02:03,708 --> 00:02:05,250
Yes, Mother.

18
00:02:09,213 --> 00:02:11,548
You are not safe.

19
00:02:18,556 --> 00:02:22,184
You may be directing this movie,
but what you're asking, we can't do.

20
00:02:23,519 --> 00:02:25,228
Don't tell me it can't be done.

21
00:02:25,396 --> 00:02:29,149
The gyro forces are too much.
You send these planes into barrel rolls ...

22
00:02:29,317 --> 00:02:32,819
... they won't make it.
- It's the climax of the picture. Make it work.

23
00:02:32,987 --> 00:02:35,489
Decrease the vertical trajectory
if you have to.

24
00:02:35,657 --> 00:02:38,158
A "Le Rhône" rotary
won't stall at 60 degrees.

25
00:02:38,326 --> 00:02:41,912
We're still short two cameras.
We need to cut that sequence down --

26
00:02:42,080 --> 00:02:45,457
We're not cutting. I'll get those cameras.
Set up for rehearsals.

27
00:02:45,625 --> 00:02:48,418
I'm Noah Dietrich.
Your office said I'd find you here.

28
00:02:48,586 --> 00:02:50,712
Dietrich.
You're a man on the come.

29
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:54,716
I read your résumé, talked to your
references. Know what I'm looking for?

30
00:02:54,884 --> 00:02:57,928
You're looking for a second-in-command
at Hughes Tools.

31
00:02:58,096 --> 00:03:00,847
Someone to oversee
the financial aspects of the business.

32
00:03:01,015 --> 00:03:03,767
I'm looking for somebody to run it
and do a good job.

33
00:03:03,935 --> 00:03:06,228
There's only one thing
you've gotta know.

34
00:03:06,396 --> 00:03:09,231
My folks, they're gone now.
So it's my money.

35
00:03:09,399 --> 00:03:13,110
What I do with that money may seem crazy
to those sons of bitches in Houston.

36
00:03:13,277 --> 00:03:16,863
I'm sure it does, but it all makes
good sense to me. You got that?

37
00:03:17,031 --> 00:03:18,824
- Got it.
- Good.

38
00:03:18,991 --> 00:03:22,119
Now, you made, what,
$5200 a year at your last job?

39
00:03:22,286 --> 00:03:26,164
- I'll pay you $10,000.
- I guess I'll be working twice as hard.

40
00:03:26,332 --> 00:03:29,918
You'll be working four times as hard.
I just got you at half price.

41
00:03:30,086 --> 00:03:31,586
- Welcome aboard.
- Thank you.

42
00:03:31,754 --> 00:03:33,922
You're my voice now.
Make them understand that.

43
00:03:34,090 --> 00:03:38,260
Some of those folks still call me Junior.
You tell them it's "Mr. Hughes" now.

44
00:03:38,428 --> 00:03:40,512
You bet.
So when do we go to Houston?

45
00:03:40,680 --> 00:03:43,974
We don't. Cholera epidemic in 1913.
Two thousand dead.

46
00:03:44,142 --> 00:03:46,184
Whole place is nothing but
pestilential swamp.

47
00:03:46,352 --> 00:03:50,480
Typhus, malaria, cholera, yellow fever.
You name it, they got it.

48
00:03:50,648 --> 00:03:52,107
You see that, Mr. Dietrich?

49
00:03:53,109 --> 00:03:57,154
You are looking at the largest
private air force in the entire world.

50
00:03:57,321 --> 00:03:59,364
What do you think of that, now?

51
00:04:00,783 --> 00:04:02,325
It's your money.

52
00:04:02,493 --> 00:04:04,911
Start them up!

53
00:05:30,873 --> 00:05:34,709
I saw the rough cut of the new
Tod Browning movie, London After Midnight.

54
00:05:34,877 --> 00:05:36,670
Lon Chaney is incredible.

55
00:05:36,838 --> 00:05:39,172
It's his best performance
in a long time.

56
00:05:39,340 --> 00:05:41,675
It's gonna be a big hit.
The cards are great.

57
00:05:41,843 --> 00:05:43,260
It's supposed to be --

58
00:05:43,427 --> 00:05:45,887
Hello, Mr. Mayer.

59
00:05:46,055 --> 00:05:49,057
I don't know if you remember me.
My name's Howard Hughes.

60
00:05:49,225 --> 00:05:51,601
I was wondering
if I could have a moment.

61
00:05:51,769 --> 00:05:54,813
- Oh, Howard Hughes. The airplane picture?
- Exactly.

62
00:05:54,981 --> 00:05:57,315
- I remember.
- Hell's Angels. You heard of it.

63
00:05:57,483 --> 00:05:58,733
- Good.
- Yes.

64
00:05:58,901 --> 00:06:01,695
I was wondering if I could
have a moment of your time.

65
00:06:01,863 --> 00:06:03,154
I need a few cameras.

66
00:06:03,990 --> 00:06:06,992
- Yeah?
- Yeah, two, to be exact.

67
00:06:07,910 --> 00:06:11,955
I bought every camera I could find.
We're shooting our big dogfight sequence.

68
00:06:12,123 --> 00:06:15,542
I need two more. Desperately.
You think MGM could help me out?

69
00:06:15,835 --> 00:06:17,085
With what?

70
00:06:17,253 --> 00:06:20,046
- Cameras.
- Oh, with the actual cam --

71
00:06:20,214 --> 00:06:23,425
We're not usually in the practice
of helping out competition.

72
00:06:23,676 --> 00:06:26,720
- No. No.
- So how many cameras do you have now?

73
00:06:26,888 --> 00:06:28,263
Twenty-four.

74
00:06:30,808 --> 00:06:33,435
You ...?
Wait a minute.

75
00:06:35,688 --> 00:06:37,564
- You have 24 cameras?
- That's right.

76
00:06:37,732 --> 00:06:40,317
- And you need --? You need two more?
- Yeah.

77
00:06:40,484 --> 00:06:44,112
- You don't think you got it with 24?
- No. No, sir.

78
00:06:44,280 --> 00:06:46,907
You know, I think --
I think we've got them all ...

79
00:06:47,074 --> 00:06:49,492
Don't we have them ...?
They're all used, right?

80
00:06:49,660 --> 00:06:51,953
- All 26 of them.
- I only need two, sir.

81
00:06:52,121 --> 00:06:53,997
- Jesus Christ, sonny.
- Howard.

82
00:06:54,165 --> 00:06:56,833
Howard. Let me give you
a little advice, huh?

83
00:06:57,001 --> 00:06:59,085
- Take your oil money --
- Drill bits.

84
00:06:59,253 --> 00:07:02,339
All right, take your drill-bit money
and put it in the bank.

85
00:07:02,506 --> 00:07:05,175
If you continue making
the movie the way you are ...

86
00:07:05,343 --> 00:07:07,636
... there isn't gonna be a distributor ...

87
00:07:07,803 --> 00:07:10,764
... you won't find anybody
who wants to see the movie ...

88
00:07:10,932 --> 00:07:13,600
... and you're not gonna have
any more oil money.

89
00:07:13,768 --> 00:07:16,811
So welcome to Hollywood.

90
00:07:16,979 --> 00:07:20,357
Yeah. Well, I'll be sure
to remember that, Mr. Mayer.

91
00:07:20,524 --> 00:07:22,359
- Good luck.
- All right.

92
00:07:22,526 --> 00:07:25,695
He needs 26 to make it work?
He's out of his mind.

93
00:07:32,954 --> 00:07:35,789
I looked down at my pants.
It was a strange situation.

94
00:07:37,625 --> 00:07:40,377
Boss.
Scram, love boat, let's go.

95
00:07:41,587 --> 00:07:44,631
- Another soda. You know what I mean.
- Milk. In the bottle.

96
00:07:44,799 --> 00:07:47,759
- With the cap still on.
- Okay, what did His Highness say?

97
00:07:47,927 --> 00:07:51,137
Son of a bitch won't part with
a single goddamn camera.

98
00:07:51,305 --> 00:07:53,848
Why don't you try and
make do with what you have.

99
00:07:54,392 --> 00:07:57,185
What I have isn't enough, John,
not for how I see it.

100
00:07:57,353 --> 00:07:58,853
Look.

101
00:07:59,021 --> 00:08:02,941
My name depends on this picture.
If it doesn't work, I'm back to Houston ...

102
00:08:03,109 --> 00:08:05,902
... making goddamn drill bits
for the rest of my life.

103
00:08:06,070 --> 00:08:08,238
Can't you do it
with the cameras you have?

104
00:08:08,406 --> 00:08:11,199
You ought to hear about
what's going on with DeMille.

105
00:08:11,367 --> 00:08:15,620
He's shooting his Bible picture.
He's gotta do a crucifixion in Fresno.

106
00:08:15,788 --> 00:08:17,038
Johnny.

107
00:08:17,206 --> 00:08:19,290
- A bunch of tractors --
- Johnny.

108
00:08:19,458 --> 00:08:21,626
- You're a press agent, are you not?
- Yeah.

109
00:08:21,794 --> 00:08:23,920
You're supposed to know
the ins and outs?

110
00:08:24,088 --> 00:08:25,338
- Absolutely.
- Do you?

111
00:08:25,506 --> 00:08:26,756
Yeah, absolutely.

112
00:08:26,924 --> 00:08:28,967
Then you leave the big ideas ...

113
00:08:29,593 --> 00:08:31,720
... to me.
- Oh, yeah. Of course, boss.

114
00:08:31,887 --> 00:08:33,638
Cigar, cigarettes, Sen-Sen?

115
00:08:34,765 --> 00:08:36,933
I thought you were
at the Brown Derby ...

116
00:08:37,101 --> 00:08:38,852
... with Trixie. No, Theresa.

117
00:08:39,020 --> 00:08:40,562
- Margaret.
- Margaret. Exactly.

118
00:08:40,730 --> 00:08:42,856
What happened to Margaret?
She lost her --

119
00:08:43,024 --> 00:08:44,566
Thank God that's settled.

120
00:08:44,734 --> 00:08:47,861
Oh, I'm sorry.
Thelma, this is Howard Hughes.

121
00:08:48,029 --> 00:08:52,032
Howard and I were discussing how he
wants me to pull a camera out of my ass.

122
00:08:52,867 --> 00:08:56,661
- Cigarette?
- Oh, no, thanks. I don't smoke.

123
00:08:59,498 --> 00:09:02,792
Boy, you are just hitting
on all six cylinders, aren't you?

124
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:04,836
My God.

125
00:09:05,463 --> 00:09:07,630
Would you do me
a favor and just ...?

126
00:09:07,798 --> 00:09:10,467
Would you just smile
for me one time? Just once?

127
00:09:13,763 --> 00:09:16,389
Yeah. Yeah. You see,
you got a short upper lip.

128
00:09:16,766 --> 00:09:18,558
Makes for a much nicer smile.

129
00:09:23,731 --> 00:09:27,317
See, I wonder what gives
a beautiful woman like you pleasure.

130
00:09:27,568 --> 00:09:31,154
I mean, say you're just standing
there, right? And I just touch you.

131
00:09:31,322 --> 00:09:33,323
Just -- Just like this.

132
00:09:33,949 --> 00:09:35,325
With my fingertips.

133
00:09:35,493 --> 00:09:37,702
Do you --?
Do you like that?

134
00:09:38,829 --> 00:09:40,413
Do you?

135
00:09:45,419 --> 00:09:48,463
You see, I wanna learn
what pleases you.

136
00:09:49,673 --> 00:09:52,717
I wanna learn everything about you.

137
00:09:52,885 --> 00:09:54,928
Would you let me do that?

138
00:09:55,096 --> 00:09:57,305
Would you give me that job?

139
00:10:02,436 --> 00:10:04,395
I'm off in a half an hour.

140
00:10:06,107 --> 00:10:08,858
- Well, I'm in room --
- 217.

141
00:10:09,026 --> 00:10:10,944
217.

142
00:10:12,947 --> 00:10:14,823
See you there.

143
00:10:19,120 --> 00:10:21,663
Johnny, get on the horn
to Universal and Warners.

144
00:10:21,831 --> 00:10:23,706
I need two more cameras
by Saturday.

145
00:10:23,874 --> 00:10:26,626
Rent them if you can.
Steal them if you have to.

146
00:10:27,378 --> 00:10:29,462
Absotively, boss.

147
00:10:29,922 --> 00:10:31,172
Absotively.

148
00:10:32,842 --> 00:10:35,593
Rumors coming from a lonely airstrip
out in Van Nuys.

149
00:10:35,761 --> 00:10:39,055
Sources whisper that young
Texas industrialist Howard Hughes ...

150
00:10:39,223 --> 00:10:41,641
... won't stop pouring money
into his war epic.

151
00:10:41,809 --> 00:10:43,226
And do we mean epic!

152
00:10:43,394 --> 00:10:46,229
One hundred and thirty-seven pilots,
87 airplanes ...

153
00:10:46,397 --> 00:10:50,775
... 35 cameramen, 2000 extras.
How long will it be before this picture ...

154
00:10:50,943 --> 00:10:53,194
... ends up costing as
much as the real war?

155
00:10:53,362 --> 00:10:55,572
Damn it.
Why the hell do they look so slow?

156
00:10:55,739 --> 00:10:59,367
This isn't what it was like up there.
They look like goddamn models!

157
00:11:07,751 --> 00:11:09,169
Son of a bitch.

158
00:11:10,462 --> 00:11:11,880
Howard?

159
00:11:14,425 --> 00:11:18,344
Without something standing
still behind the planes ...

160
00:11:18,512 --> 00:11:21,097
... we've got no idea
of how fast we're moving.

161
00:11:21,265 --> 00:11:24,100
We got no sense of relative motion.

162
00:11:25,269 --> 00:11:27,937
Call UCLA.
Get me the best meteorologist they got.

163
00:11:28,105 --> 00:11:30,190
You get him here in an hour, all right?

164
00:11:33,569 --> 00:11:36,362
Hey. You want the good news
or the bad news?

165
00:11:36,530 --> 00:11:38,114
- Bad news, always.
- All right.

166
00:11:38,282 --> 00:11:41,451
We installed the 450 radial.
Struts won't take the vibration.

167
00:11:41,619 --> 00:11:45,455
Minute we fire her up, the struts
start cracking at the attach points.

168
00:11:45,664 --> 00:11:48,416
- Well, what's the good news?
- There isn't any.

169
00:11:48,792 --> 00:11:52,420
Goddamn it, Odie. If the 450's too big,
we figure something else out.

170
00:11:52,588 --> 00:11:55,548
We've done everything.
We've rebuilt her from top to toe.

171
00:11:55,716 --> 00:11:57,508
If we drain the fuel tank ...

172
00:11:57,676 --> 00:12:01,346
... she might make 180 miles per hour.
- I want minimum 200, all right?

173
00:12:01,513 --> 00:12:04,390
I want a date with Theda Bara.
That ain't gonna happen.

174
00:12:04,558 --> 00:12:06,476
Oh, don't be so sure.

175
00:12:06,810 --> 00:12:10,688
If the struts won't sustain the engine
we need, we gotta get rid of the struts.

176
00:12:10,856 --> 00:12:12,941
No, then the top wing falls off.

177
00:12:15,653 --> 00:12:17,195
Then let it.

178
00:12:17,696 --> 00:12:19,155
What?

179
00:12:20,491 --> 00:12:22,492
Who says we need a top wing?

180
00:12:22,660 --> 00:12:24,744
I mean, who says we need anything?

181
00:12:26,914 --> 00:12:29,332
- A monoplane.
- A cantilevered monoplane, right?

182
00:12:29,500 --> 00:12:32,710
They're doing it in France.
To hell with the top wing and struts.

183
00:12:32,878 --> 00:12:35,296
- A 550 Wasp engine.
- One-hundred-octane fuel.

184
00:12:35,464 --> 00:12:38,758
- That would give us a horsepower of what?
- Seven hundred.

185
00:12:40,302 --> 00:12:44,430
We squeeze that to a thousand,
we got the fastest plane ever built.

186
00:12:47,226 --> 00:12:48,768
You know, I've gotta say ...

187
00:12:48,936 --> 00:12:52,647
... we've already spent over $200,000
rebuilding this plane.

188
00:12:54,066 --> 00:12:55,692
To hell with it.

189
00:12:56,819 --> 00:12:58,194
Tear it up, Odie.

190
00:12:58,362 --> 00:12:59,696
Go on.

191
00:13:03,367 --> 00:13:04,701
Well ...

192
00:13:07,663 --> 00:13:11,374
The cumulonimbus formations
about which you speak ...

193
00:13:12,835 --> 00:13:14,961
... that look like ...

194
00:13:15,129 --> 00:13:16,921
Giant breasts full of milk.

195
00:13:17,089 --> 00:13:18,840
I want clouds, damn it.

196
00:13:19,216 --> 00:13:20,800
Yes, clouds ...

197
00:13:20,968 --> 00:13:24,762
... that look like
giant breasts full of milk ...

198
00:13:24,930 --> 00:13:28,474
... cannot exactly be guaranteed
for any particular occasion.

199
00:13:28,642 --> 00:13:30,727
So you might have to ...

200
00:13:32,062 --> 00:13:33,396
To wait.

201
00:13:35,524 --> 00:13:37,442
Then we'll wait.

202
00:13:38,402 --> 00:13:40,737
Look, whatever they pay
you at UCLA ...

203
00:13:40,904 --> 00:13:44,532
... I'm doubling it, all right?
You work for me now. Find some clouds.

204
00:13:45,993 --> 00:13:47,368
Find some clouds.

205
00:13:48,037 --> 00:13:49,787
Find me some clouds!

206
00:13:49,955 --> 00:13:52,165
Welcome to Hell's Angels.

207
00:13:55,377 --> 00:13:56,586
Thank you.

208
00:14:05,262 --> 00:14:08,723
I've been to Chatsworth,
Santa Cruz, Encino, San Diego ...

209
00:14:08,891 --> 00:14:12,769
... Riverside, Van Nuys and Bakersfield.
It has been eight months!

210
00:14:12,936 --> 00:14:14,729
Where are my goddamn clouds, huh?

211
00:14:14,897 --> 00:14:17,231
They move, Mr. Hughes!

212
00:14:17,399 --> 00:14:18,733
Clouds move.

213
00:14:18,901 --> 00:14:21,361
- That's what they do. They move!
- You see that?

214
00:14:21,528 --> 00:14:25,239
It is costing me $5,271 a day ...

215
00:14:25,407 --> 00:14:29,786
... to keep those planes on the ground.
You find me some goddamn clouds, huh?

216
00:14:37,252 --> 00:14:38,753
Nice day.

217
00:14:39,213 --> 00:14:41,130
Yeah, very funny.

218
00:14:41,382 --> 00:14:44,217
I got a call from Houston.
They're getting nervous.

219
00:14:44,385 --> 00:14:46,302
Stop showing them the damn bills.

220
00:14:46,470 --> 00:14:47,845
That would be illegal.

221
00:14:48,013 --> 00:14:50,264
Shit, no.
Maybe it's a little bit naughty.

222
00:14:50,432 --> 00:14:54,310
Hughes Tool is incorporated in Texas.
They have to see the bills.

223
00:14:55,687 --> 00:14:59,273
Incorporate a new division out here.
We'll call it Hughes Aircraft.

224
00:14:59,441 --> 00:15:03,986
- Do we need these rivets on the cowling?
- Yeah, or the reverse thrust would rip it off.

225
00:15:04,154 --> 00:15:06,864
They're gonna give me drag.
Do something about that.

226
00:15:07,032 --> 00:15:09,325
- Wind resistance on rivets?
- I want her slippery.

227
00:15:09,493 --> 00:15:12,495
There are tax consequences
to incorporating in California.

228
00:15:12,663 --> 00:15:15,164
- Just take care of it, would you?
- Mr. Hughes!

229
00:15:15,332 --> 00:15:17,125
Oakland!

230
00:15:17,292 --> 00:15:20,336
- We have clouds in Oakland!
- You mean it this time?

231
00:15:20,504 --> 00:15:22,046
Yes!

232
00:15:22,214 --> 00:15:25,341
Goddamn it, yes.
I can promise you.

233
00:15:25,509 --> 00:15:28,761
- Clouds in Oakland.
- All right, don't get all jittery now.

234
00:15:28,929 --> 00:15:33,099
Oakland!

235
00:15:33,267 --> 00:15:36,519
We're going to Oakland!
Oakland.

236
00:16:12,681 --> 00:16:15,308
Down and to the left!

237
00:16:38,290 --> 00:16:40,291
That's perfect!

238
00:16:44,171 --> 00:16:48,591
That's right, Senator George.

239
00:16:48,759 --> 00:16:51,427
Yes, young Howard Hughes
has pulled it off!

240
00:16:51,595 --> 00:16:55,014
After two years, Hell's Angels
has finally finished filming.

241
00:16:55,182 --> 00:16:58,309
There's gonna be one heck
of a wrap party in Hollywood tonight.

242
00:16:58,477 --> 00:17:01,187
The price tag?
A staggering $2 million.

243
00:17:01,355 --> 00:17:03,856
If every human being
in America buys a ticket ...

244
00:17:04,024 --> 00:17:05,775
... he might even make a profit.

245
00:17:10,864 --> 00:17:12,198
First, clouds don't come.

246
00:17:12,366 --> 00:17:14,784
Then planes break down.
Then the planes crash.

247
00:17:16,453 --> 00:17:19,497
We've had everything but
a plague of locusts on this thing.

248
00:17:19,665 --> 00:17:21,040
I mean, you have to admit.

249
00:17:21,208 --> 00:17:25,211
Now, honestly, did you ever think
you'd actually finish the damn thing?

250
00:17:27,422 --> 00:17:28,798
Come with me.

251
00:17:30,717 --> 00:17:33,970
Mama, darling,
if I'm a success in this show ...

252
00:17:34,137 --> 00:17:36,222
... we're gonna move from here.
- Oh, no.

253
00:17:36,390 --> 00:17:38,349
Yes.
We're gonna move up in the Bronx.

254
00:17:38,517 --> 00:17:40,601
Green grass,
a lot of people you know.

255
00:17:40,769 --> 00:17:43,479
The Ginsbergs,
the Guttenbergs and the Goldbergs.

256
00:17:43,647 --> 00:17:46,315
Oh, a whole lot of "bergs."
I don't know them all.

257
00:17:46,942 --> 00:17:50,695
See, this is what the people want.
Silent pictures are yesterday's news.

258
00:17:50,862 --> 00:17:53,864
So I figure we gotta re-shoot
Hell's Angels for sound.

259
00:17:56,285 --> 00:17:57,827
How much of it?

260
00:17:57,995 --> 00:18:00,246
All of it.
Before you ask, I'll tell you.

261
00:18:00,414 --> 00:18:03,291
An additional 1.7 million.
We got that much?

262
00:18:04,418 --> 00:18:07,670
- No!
- Well, we'll make it.

263
00:18:07,838 --> 00:18:09,589
Take care of that, would you?

264
00:18:09,756 --> 00:18:11,090
Now, get this.

265
00:18:21,184 --> 00:18:23,352
In the halls of 7000 Romaine ...

266
00:18:23,520 --> 00:18:25,938
... it goes on day after day,
month after month.

267
00:18:26,106 --> 00:18:29,817
Howard Hughes is now editing
some 25 miles of film.

268
00:18:31,194 --> 00:18:35,823
Heck, I say release it now and give
the world its first 560-hour movie.

269
00:18:35,991 --> 00:18:40,244
Pat, Mr. Hughes needs this reel
in the projection room right now!

270
00:18:41,121 --> 00:18:42,705
Enough is enough, Mr. Hughes.

271
00:18:42,873 --> 00:18:46,083
Are you ever gonna let us
actually see this epic of yours?

272
00:18:46,251 --> 00:18:47,752
Hurry up!

273
00:19:08,732 --> 00:19:10,149
- Who is it?
- Noah.

274
00:19:10,317 --> 00:19:11,984
Come on in.

275
00:19:13,570 --> 00:19:16,155
I've been on the phone
to Houston for three hours.

276
00:19:16,323 --> 00:19:19,325
- We're fixing every goddamn book we have.
- Wait, wait.

277
00:19:20,243 --> 00:19:23,663
Yeah. Run reel 10 again.
I think we're duplicating a shot here.

278
00:19:23,830 --> 00:19:27,667
And tell Jimmy I want
10 chocolate chip cookies, all right?

279
00:19:27,834 --> 00:19:30,711
Medium chips,
none too close to the outside.

280
00:19:30,879 --> 00:19:32,380
Got it?

281
00:19:32,547 --> 00:19:34,882
You remember
that goddamn shot from reel 10?

282
00:19:35,050 --> 00:19:37,635
No. I don't remember
anything from reel 10.

283
00:19:37,803 --> 00:19:39,970
I don't know what reel 10 is.

284
00:19:40,138 --> 00:19:43,432
I'm a businessman, Howard.
And so are you.

285
00:19:43,600 --> 00:19:45,393
Now, look.

286
00:19:45,560 --> 00:19:47,019
This has been a great ride.

287
00:19:47,187 --> 00:19:49,105
We've had a hell of a lot of fun.

288
00:19:49,523 --> 00:19:53,192
But you're losing
$25,000 a day doing this.

289
00:19:53,485 --> 00:19:55,403
Every day.

290
00:20:00,951 --> 00:20:03,786
So, what are my options?

291
00:20:05,372 --> 00:20:08,124
Well, this time I don't know
that you have any.

292
00:20:08,291 --> 00:20:10,710
I'm afraid you gotta close it down.

293
00:20:11,461 --> 00:20:13,087
Dig your way out.

294
00:20:19,761 --> 00:20:21,762
I'm sorry, Howard.

295
00:20:22,305 --> 00:20:24,140
I truly am.

296
00:20:31,481 --> 00:20:33,107
Reel 10, Mr. Hughes.

297
00:20:39,156 --> 00:20:41,157
Mortgage Tool Co.

298
00:20:42,075 --> 00:20:47,163
- Every asset. You heard me.
- If you do that, you could lose everything.

299
00:20:47,330 --> 00:20:48,914
Well, I won't.

300
00:20:52,043 --> 00:20:53,502
I won't.

301
00:20:55,005 --> 00:20:56,797
All right.

302
00:20:58,008 --> 00:20:59,633
I'll get into it.

303
00:21:01,011 --> 00:21:02,553
Thanks, Noah.

304
00:21:37,672 --> 00:21:41,383
More than half a million souls lining
the curb of Hollywood Boulevard.

305
00:21:41,551 --> 00:21:43,219
Look at the automobiles!

306
00:21:43,386 --> 00:21:47,223
There are 45,000 cars here,
making it the greatest traffic jam ever seen.

307
00:21:47,390 --> 00:21:49,809
Howard Hughes must have
a lump in his throat.

308
00:21:49,976 --> 00:21:54,063
Six months after the stock market crashes
and after three pilots' deaths ...

309
00:21:54,231 --> 00:21:57,233
... he's finally unveiling his
$4 million baby doll.

310
00:21:57,400 --> 00:22:01,695
It's the most expensive movie ever made.
Nothing five-and-dime for our Mr. Hughes.

311
00:22:01,863 --> 00:22:05,157
Nothing like tonight has ever been
seen before, and I can say ...

312
00:22:05,325 --> 00:22:06,992
... it will never be seen again.

313
00:22:07,160 --> 00:22:11,163
Five hundred thousand people are crowding
the streets to get a glimpse of the stars.

314
00:22:11,331 --> 00:22:14,041
Three companies of Marines
were called to assist ...

315
00:22:14,209 --> 00:22:17,628
... the 250 special police who are
handling this enormous crowd --

316
00:22:17,796 --> 00:22:19,338
This is an industry town.

317
00:22:19,506 --> 00:22:22,424
And nobody but nobody
makes a movie outside a studio.

318
00:22:22,592 --> 00:22:26,095
Some Hollywood insiders over
at the Brown Derby may be laughing ...

319
00:22:26,263 --> 00:22:27,721
And now, I think ...

320
00:22:27,889 --> 00:22:30,724
Yes, yes, I can see
Mr. Hughes' car arriving now.

321
00:22:30,892 --> 00:22:33,853
Mr. Hughes escorts
the lovely starlet Jean Harlow.

322
00:22:34,020 --> 00:22:38,023
He discovered her for this picture,
and we think her platinum blond locks ...

323
00:22:38,191 --> 00:22:42,444
... and hot-jazz, baby-doll style
are gonna make her a big star.

324
00:22:51,413 --> 00:22:53,706
Howard! Howard!

325
00:23:00,255 --> 00:23:02,131
Over here!

326
00:23:08,680 --> 00:23:12,933
- This way, boss. Right over there.
- Mr. Hughes, how about a word?

327
00:23:13,143 --> 00:23:15,603
Big night for you, Mr. Hughes.

328
00:23:17,522 --> 00:23:20,149
Big night for you tonight.

329
00:23:20,317 --> 00:23:22,651
Very big. Very big.

330
00:23:22,819 --> 00:23:26,530
Tell us what it was like
making this fabulous picture.

331
00:23:28,366 --> 00:23:30,159
Yes.

332
00:23:30,327 --> 00:23:31,702
Yeah.

333
00:23:31,870 --> 00:23:34,496
So 4 million clams
from your own pocket.

334
00:23:34,664 --> 00:23:36,332
Nervous how the flick will fly?

335
00:23:39,878 --> 00:23:43,172
Big night. You enjoy the show.

336
00:23:43,673 --> 00:23:49,053
Yes, well, let me present the feminine
star of this spectacle, Hell's Angels ...

337
00:23:49,220 --> 00:23:51,847
... Miss Jean Harlow.
- Thank you.

338
00:23:52,015 --> 00:23:54,975
I would like to use this occasion
to thank Mr. Hughes ...

339
00:23:55,143 --> 00:23:58,437
... for the opportunity he gave me.
Thank you.

340
00:23:58,605 --> 00:24:01,982
Thank you!
Now I'd like to ask Roscoe Arbuckle ...

341
00:24:02,150 --> 00:24:05,110
... to introduce
his pet lion cub, Gilmore.

342
00:24:05,278 --> 00:24:07,947
What's the matter with you?
Can't remember my name?

343
00:24:08,114 --> 00:24:12,117
I'm sorry. Roscoe Turner,
and this would be Gilmore.

344
00:24:55,245 --> 00:24:56,912
It's going! It's going!

345
00:24:58,581 --> 00:25:02,001
Murder! That's what this
dirty, rotten politician war is, murder!

346
00:25:02,168 --> 00:25:03,627
You know it as well as I do.

347
00:25:41,416 --> 00:25:43,000
Stand up, slim, take a bow.

348
00:25:56,639 --> 00:25:58,849
Reel four played too long.
Too many coughs.

349
00:25:59,017 --> 00:26:02,978
Get the team out of the party and
to the office. I wanna cut a few shots.

350
00:26:03,146 --> 00:26:05,397
Oh, find Glenn.
Somebody write this down.

351
00:26:05,565 --> 00:26:06,815
Flush rivets.
Got that?

352
00:26:06,983 --> 00:26:08,650
- Flush rivets.
- Flush rivets.

353
00:26:08,818 --> 00:26:10,360
Lickety-split, boss.

354
00:26:10,612 --> 00:26:12,237
Here he is! Here he is!

355
00:26:14,324 --> 00:26:16,200
Variety says, "This one won't miss!"

356
00:26:16,367 --> 00:26:19,661
- Magnificently photographed!
- Awesome beyond description!

357
00:26:19,829 --> 00:26:23,415
The most extraordinary output
to emerge from a motion-picture studio.

358
00:26:23,583 --> 00:26:26,502
Not for a long time have I seen
anything as enthralling.

359
00:26:26,669 --> 00:26:29,713
It costs 4 million dollars
and has 4 million thrills!

360
00:26:29,881 --> 00:26:32,174
- Majestically ...
- Most epic picture of its time!

361
00:27:27,647 --> 00:27:30,607
A lighter shade. I don't want
to look like Boris Karloff.

362
00:27:30,775 --> 00:27:32,401
If you know what I mean.

363
00:27:34,320 --> 00:27:38,240
I read in the magazines
that you play golf.

364
00:27:38,408 --> 00:27:40,075
On occasion.

365
00:27:40,243 --> 00:27:42,494
Well, how about nine holes?

366
00:27:44,581 --> 00:27:46,748
Now, Mr. Hughes?

367
00:27:47,417 --> 00:27:50,169
If it would be convenient, Miss Hepburn.

368
00:28:12,734 --> 00:28:16,195
You're not extending
enough on your follow-through.

369
00:28:16,362 --> 00:28:19,281
Follow-through
is everything in golf, just like life.

370
00:28:19,449 --> 00:28:20,782
Don't you find?

371
00:28:20,950 --> 00:28:22,951
Saw your Scarface picture.

372
00:28:23,119 --> 00:28:24,453
- Violent.
- Realistic.

373
00:28:24,621 --> 00:28:26,955
Movies are movies, Howard.
Not life.

374
00:28:27,123 --> 00:28:28,790
Now the stage.

375
00:28:28,958 --> 00:28:30,209
The stage is real.

376
00:28:30,376 --> 00:28:34,379
Real flesh and blood. Human beings
right out there in front of you, buster.

377
00:28:34,547 --> 00:28:37,507
Can't look away. Can't munch popcorn.
That would be rude.

378
00:28:37,675 --> 00:28:38,967
Do you like the theater?

379
00:28:39,260 --> 00:28:41,762
- No.
- Oh, I adore the theater.

380
00:28:41,930 --> 00:28:44,097
Only alive on-stage.
I'll teach you.

381
00:28:44,265 --> 00:28:48,185
We'll see some Ibsen. If the Republicans
haven't outlawed him by now.

382
00:28:48,353 --> 00:28:51,396
You're not a Republican, are you?
How did you vote in '32?

383
00:28:51,564 --> 00:28:55,025
- Well, I didn't.
- You must! It's your sacred franchise.

384
00:28:58,905 --> 00:29:01,657
Heard you were wooing Ginger Rogers.
What about that?

385
00:29:01,824 --> 00:29:04,159
She's just a friend.

386
00:29:04,327 --> 00:29:06,036
Men can't be friends with women.

387
00:29:06,204 --> 00:29:08,288
They must possess them
or leave them be.

388
00:29:08,456 --> 00:29:11,583
It's a primitive urge from caveman days.
It's all in Darwin.

389
00:29:11,751 --> 00:29:17,089
Hunt the flesh, kill the flesh, eat the flesh.
That's the male sex all over.

390
00:29:17,757 --> 00:29:19,132
Excuse me?

391
00:29:19,926 --> 00:29:22,928
Well, if you're deaf,
you must own up to it.

392
00:29:23,179 --> 00:29:25,138
Get a hearing aid.
Or see my father.

393
00:29:25,306 --> 00:29:28,976
He's a urologist, but it's all tied up
inside the body, don't you find?

394
00:29:29,310 --> 00:29:30,769
Me, I keep healthy.

395
00:29:30,937 --> 00:29:33,063
I take seven showers a day
to keep clean.

396
00:29:33,231 --> 00:29:36,566
Also because I am what's so
vulgarly referred to as "outdoorsy."

397
00:29:36,734 --> 00:29:40,737
I'm not outdoorsy.
I'm athletic. I sweat.

398
00:29:40,905 --> 00:29:43,699
There it is.
Now we both know the sordid truth.

399
00:29:43,866 --> 00:29:46,326
I sweat and you're deaf.

400
00:29:46,494 --> 00:29:49,371
Aren't we a fine pair of misfits?

401
00:29:52,917 --> 00:29:54,793
Three.

402
00:30:02,343 --> 00:30:04,177
Noble effort.

403
00:30:06,556 --> 00:30:09,224
So I suppose you're
wooing me now?

404
00:30:09,892 --> 00:30:11,893
Oh, well.

405
00:30:30,955 --> 00:30:32,456
Not enough.

406
00:30:33,041 --> 00:30:36,084
Not enough.
These rivets have to be completely flush.

407
00:30:36,252 --> 00:30:39,129
I want every screw and joint countersunk.

408
00:30:39,380 --> 00:30:42,174
I want no wind resistance
on the fuselage.

409
00:30:42,342 --> 00:30:44,634
She has got to be clean, Odie.

410
00:30:44,802 --> 00:30:46,595
- Clean. Understand?
- Okay, Howard.

411
00:30:46,763 --> 00:30:48,555
I don't know
what else to tell you.

412
00:30:49,599 --> 00:30:53,185
- What do you got for me?
- The thing is, TWA needs a new plane.

413
00:30:53,353 --> 00:30:55,979
- A modern plane.
- Oh, yeah? What kind of plane?

414
00:30:56,147 --> 00:30:58,398
Okay. The DC-3 has 21 daytime seats ...

415
00:30:58,566 --> 00:31:00,984
... and 14 overnight berths.
- Something bigger?

416
00:31:02,320 --> 00:31:04,696
Try 50 seats with
a ceiling of 12,000 feet.

417
00:31:04,864 --> 00:31:07,115
No. No, 20,000.

418
00:31:07,450 --> 00:31:09,618
Think about it.
What does 20,000 feet give you?

419
00:31:09,786 --> 00:31:12,371
- Less turbulence.
- Because it's above the weather.

420
00:31:12,538 --> 00:31:14,915
Jack, we wanna fly
above the weather.

421
00:31:15,083 --> 00:31:18,627
Only 1 percent of the American population
has set foot on an airliner.

422
00:31:18,795 --> 00:31:21,588
Why? Because they're scared to death.
They should be.

423
00:31:21,756 --> 00:31:24,341
I mean, 7000 feet is bumpy as shit.
You know that.

424
00:31:24,509 --> 00:31:27,010
We build a plane
that flies above the weather ...

425
00:31:27,178 --> 00:31:30,972
... we could get every man, woman
and child in this country to feel safe.

426
00:31:31,140 --> 00:31:35,644
An airplane with the ability to fly into
the sub-stratosphere across the country.

427
00:31:35,812 --> 00:31:37,646
Across the world.

428
00:31:37,814 --> 00:31:39,898
Now that is the future.

429
00:31:40,316 --> 00:31:41,566
- You with me?
- Yeah.

430
00:31:41,734 --> 00:31:45,654
I don't wanna get into this
if your board doesn't have the balls for it.

431
00:31:45,822 --> 00:31:48,156
- Would they support us?
- I don't know.

432
00:31:48,324 --> 00:31:50,534
- What's your financial picture?
- Not great.

433
00:31:50,701 --> 00:31:52,869
- Last year's deficit?
- 770,000.

434
00:31:53,037 --> 00:31:55,747
- What's it selling at?
- About 8 dollars a share.

435
00:31:55,915 --> 00:31:57,666
That's the lowest it's been, huh?

436
00:31:59,627 --> 00:32:01,086
I could do that.

437
00:32:01,254 --> 00:32:02,754
- Do what?
- Buy it.

438
00:32:02,922 --> 00:32:05,590
- You wanna buy the airline?
- For crying out loud ...

439
00:32:05,758 --> 00:32:09,678
... we don't want pencil pushers getting
in the way of us making our plane.

440
00:32:09,846 --> 00:32:13,682
Give me brass tacks, now. What does
controlling interest in TWA cost me?

441
00:32:14,684 --> 00:32:16,101
Call it 15 million.

442
00:32:18,521 --> 00:32:20,689
That is a chunk of change, huh?

443
00:32:24,110 --> 00:32:25,944
You call Noah Dietrich.

444
00:32:26,112 --> 00:32:28,071
You have him start buying.

445
00:32:28,239 --> 00:32:29,531
Howard, hold on.

446
00:32:29,699 --> 00:32:32,701
Are you sure?
You wanna think about it for five minutes?

447
00:32:32,869 --> 00:32:36,705
Hell, Jack, I got a tiger by the tail here.
I ain't gonna let it go.

448
00:32:45,548 --> 00:32:47,257
Good evening, Mr. Hughes.

449
00:32:47,425 --> 00:32:49,801
Welcome. Your table is ready.

450
00:32:50,970 --> 00:32:52,512
How goes the aviation?

451
00:32:52,680 --> 00:32:55,640
- Oh, just fine, Pete.
- I'm so glad.

452
00:32:57,977 --> 00:32:59,311
Good evening, Mr. Hughes.

453
00:32:59,479 --> 00:33:00,729
- Madame.
- It's "miss."

454
00:33:00,897 --> 00:33:03,315
Miss. The usual, Mr. Hughes?

455
00:33:03,483 --> 00:33:05,609
- Please.
- May I recommend for the lady ...

456
00:33:05,776 --> 00:33:09,279
... our clementine soup followed
by roast duck with currant glaze ...

457
00:33:09,447 --> 00:33:12,407
... and poached pears in rose sauce.
It's truly divine.

458
00:33:12,575 --> 00:33:14,075
Yeah. That sounds fine.

459
00:33:16,245 --> 00:33:18,997
Your kind of joint, is it?

460
00:33:20,124 --> 00:33:21,708
Wouldn't have thought.

461
00:33:21,876 --> 00:33:25,086
They're open late.
I go to a hot-dog stand on "La Cienega" too.

462
00:33:25,254 --> 00:33:27,923
- They're open till about 4.
- Are they?

463
00:33:29,926 --> 00:33:31,760
How marvelous.

464
00:33:47,610 --> 00:33:49,277
Howard! Howard!

465
00:33:50,238 --> 00:33:52,989
Hi! Son of a gun.

466
00:33:53,157 --> 00:33:56,993
Kate, this is Johnny Meyer.
I suppose you could call him my press agent.

467
00:33:57,161 --> 00:33:59,454
- Pleased to meet you. Loved Alice Adams.
- You're too kind.

468
00:33:59,622 --> 00:34:02,290
- I'm sure you know Errol, right?
- Mr. Flynn. Yes.

469
00:34:02,458 --> 00:34:07,337
Kate. Kate. Kate of the clenched-jawed
Hepburns. Enchanting as always.

470
00:34:07,505 --> 00:34:10,215
You should use Lux on your hands,
by the way. I do.

471
00:34:10,383 --> 00:34:12,551
You and Howard
ought to cook up a picture.

472
00:34:12,718 --> 00:34:15,262
Co-star with Errol.
I could sell that in spades.

473
00:34:15,429 --> 00:34:17,639
That would be marvelous. Howard?

474
00:34:18,224 --> 00:34:21,977
I think not.
Don't you read Variety, Mr. Meyer?

475
00:34:22,144 --> 00:34:25,814
Well, I'm box-office poison.
I'm on the outs, the skids, the doldrums.

476
00:34:25,982 --> 00:34:29,359
Washed-up, day-old fish
not worth the eating, so they tell me.

477
00:34:29,527 --> 00:34:33,363
Hell with them. Hell with them, my dear.
Soulless pricks to a man, right?

478
00:34:33,531 --> 00:34:37,576
Johnny tells me you're thinking about
doing a Western, of all goddamn things.

479
00:34:41,664 --> 00:34:44,416
Are you making a Western, Howard?

480
00:34:44,625 --> 00:34:47,377
Yeah. Making a Western.
I'm gonna call it The Outlaw.

481
00:34:47,545 --> 00:34:49,713
Yeah. And you know
what it's about? S-E-X.

482
00:34:49,880 --> 00:34:52,591
- It's all about S-E-X.
- It's a Western.

483
00:34:52,758 --> 00:34:55,677
You can't have fornication in a Western.
It isn't done.

484
00:34:55,845 --> 00:34:57,637
It's not real sex, it's movie sex.

485
00:34:57,805 --> 00:35:01,474
What Scarface did for the gangster picture,
The Outlaw will do for the Western.

486
00:35:01,642 --> 00:35:04,519
Put the sex and guts and blood
up there on the screen.

487
00:35:04,687 --> 00:35:06,688
- Have you seen my cigarettes?
- Don't mind us.

488
00:35:06,856 --> 00:35:10,275
New York cut steak, 12 peas,
bottle of milk with the cap on.

489
00:35:10,443 --> 00:35:13,695
- You can't afford your own cigarettes?
- Jack has all my money.

490
00:35:13,863 --> 00:35:18,158
I hope your food isn't getting cold
at your table somewhere or something.

491
00:35:18,326 --> 00:35:20,619
No, no. We're here all night.
Don't worry.

492
00:35:20,786 --> 00:35:26,333
Now, Howard. Now, Howard. If you're
seriously talking about putting carnality ...

493
00:35:26,500 --> 00:35:31,171
... back on the silver screen, you must swear
to let me in on the casting session.

494
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:39,179
- I have an eye for talent. Isn't that right?
- You ought to give up prancing in tights ...

495
00:35:39,347 --> 00:35:42,932
... be a talent scout.
- That prancing paid for my new yacht.

496
00:35:43,100 --> 00:35:46,561
You must all come sailing with me.
Catalina. What do you say?

497
00:35:46,729 --> 00:35:49,898
- Catalina. Sounds grand. Yeah.
- I've even managed to coax ...

498
00:35:50,066 --> 00:35:53,943
... the luscious Miss De Havilland
and her equally luscious sister to come.

499
00:35:54,111 --> 00:35:58,990
Though I fear their mother will insist on
coming, to preserve their questionable virtue.

500
00:35:59,158 --> 00:36:03,370
We shall assault these twin monuments
of pristine Britannic beauty nonetheless.

501
00:36:03,537 --> 00:36:05,580
- What do you say, Howard?
- Yeah?

502
00:36:05,998 --> 00:36:08,166
- Yeah. Yeah.
- Yeah?

503
00:36:12,463 --> 00:36:13,755
I gotta go.

504
00:36:14,632 --> 00:36:18,176
If you'll excuse us, we have --
We have to be somewhere.

505
00:36:18,511 --> 00:36:20,970
You are somewhere, Howard,
you madman.

506
00:36:21,138 --> 00:36:24,182
- Somewhere else. Excuse us.
- Charmed, gentlemen.

507
00:36:24,350 --> 00:36:27,977
Do help yourself to the poached pears.
I hear they're divine.

508
00:36:28,604 --> 00:36:31,398
Well. Howard Hughes,
ladies and gentlemen.

509
00:36:32,274 --> 00:36:33,608
Was that meant for me?

510
00:36:33,776 --> 00:36:37,112
My hero. God, all that
Hollywood talk bores me silly.

511
00:36:37,279 --> 00:36:40,281
As if there aren't more important things,
like Mussolini.

512
00:36:40,449 --> 00:36:44,369
- Where are we going, by the way?
- Do you feel like a little adventure?

513
00:36:44,537 --> 00:36:46,454
Do your worst, Mr. Hughes.

514
00:36:46,622 --> 00:36:50,834
- Think you own this place, you limey bastard?
- I'm a Tasmanian bastard, you prick.

515
00:36:51,001 --> 00:36:53,420
- Thataway, Errol.
- Let me at him!

516
00:37:26,996 --> 00:37:29,706
That's Mr. Mayer's house right there.

517
00:37:29,874 --> 00:37:31,791
Do you know where Jack Warner lives?

518
00:37:41,051 --> 00:37:44,846
- What's that on the steering wheel?
- Cellophane.

519
00:37:45,014 --> 00:37:48,892
If you had any idea of the crap
that people carry around on their hands.

520
00:37:49,435 --> 00:37:51,060
What kind of crap?

521
00:37:51,771 --> 00:37:53,438
You don't wanna know.

522
00:37:58,694 --> 00:38:00,653
Hold on to the wheel for a bit.

523
00:38:08,704 --> 00:38:11,873
That's too hard. Relax your hand.
Relax your hand.

524
00:38:17,546 --> 00:38:22,509
You see, you gotta feel the vibration
of the engine through your fingertips.

525
00:38:22,676 --> 00:38:25,720
- Do you feel that?
- Yes.

526
00:38:28,349 --> 00:38:30,016
Well, that's good.

527
00:38:30,643 --> 00:38:32,352
Golly!

528
00:38:36,732 --> 00:38:38,566
Well, she's all yours.

529
00:38:38,776 --> 00:38:42,445
- Where are you going?!
- I think there's some milk back here.

530
00:38:43,447 --> 00:38:46,241
- You just keep us steady, now.
- All right.

531
00:39:05,261 --> 00:39:07,095
- Howard.
- Yeah?

532
00:39:07,263 --> 00:39:10,223
There's a rather alarming mountain
heading our way.

533
00:39:10,391 --> 00:39:12,600
Pull back on the wheel a smidge.
Go on.

534
00:39:17,439 --> 00:39:20,024
Golly!

535
00:39:25,573 --> 00:39:30,743
I don't think I've ever met someone
who actually uses the word "golly."

536
00:39:37,960 --> 00:39:40,461
You all right?
Do you want me to take over?

537
00:39:40,629 --> 00:39:42,630
Just when I'm getting the hang of it?

538
00:39:47,970 --> 00:39:51,681
- You want some milk?
- Oh, please.

539
00:40:13,621 --> 00:40:15,830
Utterly smashing!
We'll do it again.

540
00:40:15,998 --> 00:40:19,167
I'm free Wednesday.
It's a little early for golf, though.

541
00:40:19,335 --> 00:40:21,628
Oh, no, no. I live right there.

542
00:40:22,129 --> 00:40:24,672
- Feel like a drink?
- Lead on.

543
00:40:25,883 --> 00:40:29,093
Now, that makes
for a challenging par four.

544
00:40:29,345 --> 00:40:33,014
My decorator
picked out the wallpaper and such.

545
00:40:33,682 --> 00:40:35,725
He's queer as a bedbug.

546
00:40:35,893 --> 00:40:38,645
But I just hate this room.

547
00:40:38,938 --> 00:40:40,772
Gives me the willies.

548
00:40:41,273 --> 00:40:45,360
Like I'm about to be swallowed up
by the latest issue of Town & Country.

549
00:40:54,036 --> 00:40:55,787
What room do you like?

550
00:40:57,039 --> 00:40:58,539
My study.

551
00:41:00,918 --> 00:41:02,585
Take me there.

552
00:41:18,936 --> 00:41:21,980
You are the tallest woman I know.

553
00:41:22,898 --> 00:41:27,026
And all sharp elbows and knees.
Beware.

554
00:41:49,550 --> 00:41:52,593
Will you fly me to work tomorrow?

555
00:41:55,222 --> 00:41:57,432
It is tomorrow.

556
00:42:50,194 --> 00:42:53,988
Keep your eye on the fuel. She's got
a minimum to keep her weight down.

557
00:42:54,156 --> 00:42:57,158
Two runs. That's it.
After that, you're flying on vapors.

558
00:42:57,326 --> 00:43:00,119
And then you crash and you die.
Give her easy flying.

559
00:43:00,287 --> 00:43:03,581
Don't worry about speed
and don't think about the record today.

560
00:43:03,749 --> 00:43:07,210
I wish you'd let someone else take her.
You've got 20 test pilots.

561
00:43:07,377 --> 00:43:11,714
Hell, why should I let someone else
have all the fun? See you in a bit.

562
00:43:32,694 --> 00:43:34,445
Contact!

563
00:45:04,077 --> 00:45:05,286
339.

564
00:45:07,414 --> 00:45:09,290
Goddamn!

565
00:45:30,979 --> 00:45:32,521
347.

566
00:45:33,982 --> 00:45:35,274
Son of a bitch!

567
00:46:07,641 --> 00:46:10,184
- 352.
- 352!

568
00:46:11,436 --> 00:46:12,687
Good girl.

569
00:46:22,447 --> 00:46:24,156
Damn it!

570
00:46:27,953 --> 00:46:30,079
Goddamn it!

571
00:46:30,539 --> 00:46:32,748
- Oh, God!
- There goes our meal ticket.

572
00:46:32,916 --> 00:46:34,417
Come on!

573
00:47:14,583 --> 00:47:16,000
Howard!

574
00:47:16,168 --> 00:47:18,336
- Howard!
- How did we do?

575
00:47:19,421 --> 00:47:21,756
352 on the last run.

576
00:47:23,550 --> 00:47:25,176
She'll go faster.

577
00:47:25,761 --> 00:47:27,386
Country mouse!

578
00:47:28,138 --> 00:47:31,557
- Kate! Katie!
- Upstairs, city mouse.

579
00:47:34,644 --> 00:47:37,563
Hello.
Good Lord, what happened to you?

580
00:47:37,731 --> 00:47:39,940
Oh, nothing. A hard landing.
I cut my foot.

581
00:47:40,108 --> 00:47:43,152
Sit down. I'll take care of it.
You tell me everything.

582
00:47:43,320 --> 00:47:47,156
You cannot imagine what it was like, Katie.
You cannot imagine the speed.

583
00:47:47,324 --> 00:47:50,493
- She was like a winged bullet up there.
- What did she make?

584
00:47:50,660 --> 00:47:54,830
Oh, around 352.

585
00:48:01,797 --> 00:48:03,297
You did it!

586
00:48:04,633 --> 00:48:06,467
Fastest man on the planet.

587
00:48:06,635 --> 00:48:09,887
Hot dog! I'm so proud of you.

588
00:48:10,055 --> 00:48:12,056
- She did it, baby.
- You knew she would.

589
00:48:12,224 --> 00:48:15,184
Oh, she was fine. She was just fine.

590
00:48:16,395 --> 00:48:17,978
Now let me see your foot.

591
00:48:18,188 --> 00:48:19,480
Yeah.

592
00:48:20,190 --> 00:48:23,776
- Good God! You're covered in blood.
- Oh, no. That's just beet juice.

593
00:48:23,944 --> 00:48:26,112
- I crashed into a beet field.
- What?

594
00:48:26,279 --> 00:48:28,489
Yeah, I crashed in a beet field.

595
00:48:31,660 --> 00:48:33,786
Let me get you cleaned up.

596
00:48:34,788 --> 00:48:39,333
- Heavens, what is this? Electrical tape?
- Yeah. Odie just sort of slammed it on there.

597
00:48:40,335 --> 00:48:45,381
But all I could think about
was getting home to see you.

598
00:48:50,095 --> 00:48:52,972
I am so proud of you.

599
00:48:57,519 --> 00:48:59,854
Now, this is gonna sting a little bit.

600
00:49:00,021 --> 00:49:03,858
Oh, this is useless.
Come to the bathroom.

601
00:49:05,068 --> 00:49:07,945
- Don't get beet juice on the carpet.
- I won't, I won't.

602
00:49:08,113 --> 00:49:10,781
- Too hot!
- Don't be a baby.

603
00:49:12,451 --> 00:49:15,286
Was the press there?

604
00:49:16,204 --> 00:49:17,496
Some.

605
00:49:17,706 --> 00:49:22,835
But they're calling everyone.
Should be on the wires by now.

606
00:49:31,428 --> 00:49:33,012
What is it?

607
00:49:35,724 --> 00:49:37,308
Kate?

608
00:49:40,562 --> 00:49:43,647
I've been famous,
for better or worse ...

609
00:49:44,191 --> 00:49:46,150
... for a long time now ...

610
00:49:46,318 --> 00:49:50,654
... and I wonder if you know what it ...

611
00:49:51,281 --> 00:49:53,073
... really means.

612
00:49:54,242 --> 00:49:57,369
Yeah. I had my fair share
of press on Hell's Angels.

613
00:49:58,121 --> 00:49:59,914
I'm used to it.

614
00:50:01,875 --> 00:50:03,584
Are you?

615
00:50:07,255 --> 00:50:09,006
Howard, we're ...

616
00:50:11,927 --> 00:50:14,386
We're not like everyone else.

617
00:50:16,389 --> 00:50:21,310
Too many acute angles.
Too many eccentricities.

618
00:50:22,103 --> 00:50:24,939
We have to be very careful not to ...

619
00:50:26,274 --> 00:50:30,110
... let people in,
or they'll make us into freaks.

620
00:50:31,279 --> 00:50:35,866
Kate, they can't get in here.
We're safe.

621
00:50:37,577 --> 00:50:39,453
They can always get in.

622
00:50:41,623 --> 00:50:45,042
When my brother killed himself ...

623
00:50:46,211 --> 00:50:48,796
... there were photographers
at the funeral.

624
00:50:50,006 --> 00:50:52,258
There's no decency to it.

625
00:51:04,688 --> 00:51:06,772
You know, sometimes I ...

626
00:51:10,485 --> 00:51:12,653
I get these feelings, Katie.

627
00:51:17,659 --> 00:51:20,202
I get these ideas, these ...

628
00:51:23,039 --> 00:51:25,666
... crazy ideas about ...

629
00:51:28,086 --> 00:51:30,462
... things that may not ...

630
00:51:31,715 --> 00:51:34,592
Things that may not really be there.

631
00:51:35,260 --> 00:51:36,802
Yeah.

632
00:51:43,476 --> 00:51:46,228
Sometimes I truly fear that I'm ...

633
00:51:48,273 --> 00:51:50,232
... losing my mind.

634
00:51:57,824 --> 00:51:59,700
And if I did, it would ...

635
00:52:02,787 --> 00:52:05,164
It'd be like flying blind.

636
00:52:13,298 --> 00:52:14,965
You understand?

637
00:52:19,137 --> 00:52:21,930
You taught me to fly, Howard.

638
00:52:24,893 --> 00:52:26,894
I'll take the wheel.

639
00:52:42,827 --> 00:52:46,872
Smashing all records, Howard Hughes
outdoes Jules Verne's wildest dreams.

640
00:52:47,165 --> 00:52:50,417
Around the world from New York
to New York in four days.

641
00:52:50,585 --> 00:52:53,545
Even beating Wiley Post's mark
by over three days.

642
00:52:53,713 --> 00:52:56,924
New aviation history is written
when his Lockheed monoplane ...

643
00:52:57,092 --> 00:53:00,094
... returns swiftly and safely.
A daring aviator.

644
00:53:00,553 --> 00:53:03,222
A true pioneer of the world's airways.

645
00:53:03,390 --> 00:53:07,393
From New York to Paris, he cuts Lindbergh's
time in half. Then on to Moscow.

646
00:53:07,560 --> 00:53:12,106
Thirty-five hours out of New York,
he roars across Siberia's trackless wastes.

647
00:53:12,273 --> 00:53:16,944
Sixty hours out of New York, he heads
for Alaska, most hazardous hop of all.

648
00:53:17,112 --> 00:53:19,488
Continuing the terrific pace,
he comes home ...

649
00:53:19,656 --> 00:53:21,990
... bringing new laurels
to American aviation.

650
00:53:23,326 --> 00:53:26,620
Howard Hughes and his crew
may find more worlds to conquer --

651
00:53:33,420 --> 00:53:37,965
You won't believe this. It just came over the
wires. Hughes has bought control of TWA.

652
00:53:40,719 --> 00:53:43,595
I thought Mr. Hughes
was flying around the world.

653
00:53:43,805 --> 00:53:47,182
Apparently he did it while he was flying,
over the radio.

654
00:53:54,399 --> 00:53:57,693
I have heard some disquieting rumors
about Mr. Hughes.

655
00:53:59,279 --> 00:54:02,698
I'd like to know everything
there is to know about Mr. Hughes.

656
00:54:05,160 --> 00:54:07,369
I'd like you to attend to that for me.

657
00:54:08,371 --> 00:54:09,997
Thoroughly.

658
00:54:10,582 --> 00:54:13,000
The Pantages is glittering tonight.

659
00:54:13,168 --> 00:54:16,003
- Howard!
- Right over here. This way, over to the left.

660
00:54:16,171 --> 00:54:18,839
- Mr. Hughes, how was your flight?
- Miss Hepburn!

661
00:54:19,007 --> 00:54:21,675
- When are you gonna name the day?
- Raise your head.

662
00:54:21,843 --> 00:54:24,011
What's the next movie?
Give us the scoop.

663
00:54:24,179 --> 00:54:26,847
Right here. How many more
records are you gonna set?

664
00:54:27,015 --> 00:54:30,350
Right over here. Come on.
Give us a smile. It won't kill you.

665
00:54:30,518 --> 00:54:32,394
- Howard, this way.
- Beautiful.

666
00:54:32,562 --> 00:54:35,063
Over here, over here, Mr. Hughes.

667
00:54:35,231 --> 00:54:37,691
When are you gonna fly
around the world again?

668
00:54:37,859 --> 00:54:41,862
You gonna fly with Kate next time?
Did you get lonely without her?

669
00:54:42,030 --> 00:54:46,074
- Talk to Lindbergh about your flight yet?
- Where's Linda Darnell tonight?

670
00:54:46,242 --> 00:54:49,536
- Please, Mr. Hughes.
- Right here. Right here, Mr. Hughes.

671
00:54:49,704 --> 00:54:52,206
Are you trying to be more famous
than Lindbergh?

672
00:54:52,916 --> 00:54:56,668
You know,
fame is supposed to be my turf.

673
00:54:58,880 --> 00:55:00,547
L.B.!

674
00:55:03,176 --> 00:55:06,553
If you don't get more distinguished
every time I see you.

675
00:55:06,721 --> 00:55:08,722
You look so beautiful.

676
00:55:16,523 --> 00:55:18,148
Is that true?

677
00:55:26,950 --> 00:55:28,826
Don't worry about it, Howard.

678
00:55:28,993 --> 00:55:32,663
She's just working the room.
It's her job, baby.

679
00:55:35,708 --> 00:55:39,503
Sultry Southern tigress Ava Gardner
dazzles the room tonight.

680
00:55:39,671 --> 00:55:41,922
She's the newest star
in the MGM galaxy.

681
00:55:42,090 --> 00:55:45,717
And believe you me,
she puts the "cheese" in "cheesecake."

682
00:55:47,929 --> 00:55:53,475
Well, Jane Eyre has been selling popcorn
for over a hundred years, L.B.

683
00:56:34,225 --> 00:56:38,854
Hello.

684
00:56:44,068 --> 00:56:46,945
Could you reach me a towel?

685
00:56:54,370 --> 00:56:56,121
I ...

686
00:56:57,248 --> 00:57:00,500
I really can't do that.

687
00:57:02,128 --> 00:57:03,670
I'm sorry.

688
00:57:28,488 --> 00:57:32,824
I'm an idiot. I'm a complete idiot,
and I'm sorry.

689
00:57:33,159 --> 00:57:36,745
- Forget it.
- No, no. I'm a vain, preening ass ...

690
00:57:36,913 --> 00:57:41,917
... without a single redeeming feature.
- That's not true. You have very good teeth.

691
00:57:42,418 --> 00:57:43,877
Come on.

692
00:57:44,754 --> 00:57:49,091
I've got a better idea. Take me flying.
Or better yet, I'll take you flying.

693
00:57:49,258 --> 00:57:51,009
Do your worst, Miss Hepburn.

694
00:58:00,103 --> 00:58:03,939
Don't be so squirmy. You're gonna
get on famously with Father and Mother.

695
00:58:04,107 --> 00:58:07,734
And I'm sure they'll like you too.
Once they get to know you.

696
00:58:16,077 --> 00:58:18,870
- Hello! Hello!
- Kath, hello.

697
00:58:19,038 --> 00:58:20,580
Kathy.

698
00:58:23,543 --> 00:58:27,254
- Who's that with the camera right there?
- That's my ex-husband, Ludlow.

699
00:58:27,422 --> 00:58:29,715
Father and Mother are just mad
about Luddie.

700
00:58:29,882 --> 00:58:34,219
- What the hell's he doing here?
- Oh, he's here all the time.

701
00:58:35,096 --> 00:58:36,763
Hello!

702
00:58:38,266 --> 00:58:39,725
Sorry we're late.

703
00:58:39,892 --> 00:58:42,185
- Mom.
- Oh. Oh, thank you.

704
00:58:42,353 --> 00:58:43,979
- Dad.
- Darling.

705
00:58:44,147 --> 00:58:47,441
- Uncle Willy.
- Oh, who have we got here?

706
00:58:47,608 --> 00:58:50,360
- Don't feel self-conscious.
- Hepburns! Hepburns!

707
00:58:50,528 --> 00:58:54,281
Attention, please. This is Howard.

708
00:58:54,574 --> 00:58:56,408
Howard, welcome.

709
00:58:57,744 --> 00:58:59,828
Don't worry, he's had his lunch.

710
00:59:01,456 --> 00:59:03,331
He likes you. That's unusual.

711
00:59:03,499 --> 00:59:06,835
We pay our devotion to the arts here.
A colony we created.

712
00:59:07,003 --> 00:59:10,964
Julian's a painter. Abstract, of course.
What's the point of painting ...

713
00:59:11,132 --> 00:59:14,509
... something real when you can just
take a picture nowadays?

714
