You missed it. Right there.

943
01:14:35,013 --> 01:14:36,889
Clean it off, would you?

944
01:14:37,057 --> 01:14:39,558
Here. Thanks.

945
01:14:42,813 --> 01:14:44,230
No, throw it away.

946
01:14:48,276 --> 01:14:49,694
No, over there.

947
01:14:56,201 --> 01:15:00,037
Thanks. So, what do you call her?

948
01:15:00,205 --> 01:15:02,373
The Constellation,
but we can change that.

949
01:15:02,541 --> 01:15:04,166
No, no.

950
01:15:04,334 --> 01:15:07,378
It's pretty. I like her.

951
01:15:08,338 --> 01:15:10,423
So, what kind of deal can you give me?

952
01:15:10,590 --> 01:15:12,425
What kind of deal can you give me?

953
01:15:12,592 --> 01:15:14,885
The first 40 planes off the assembly line.

954
01:15:15,053 --> 01:15:17,596
That should give us about
two years' exclusivity.

955
01:15:17,764 --> 01:15:19,056
Hell, more than that.

956
01:15:19,224 --> 01:15:23,227
United and American don't have
the imagination for a plane like this.

957
01:15:23,395 --> 01:15:25,980
Two years ahead of Juan Trippe, then.

958
01:15:31,028 --> 01:15:32,278
How much?

959
01:15:32,446 --> 01:15:34,613
Four hundred and fifty thousand each.

960
01:15:35,449 --> 01:15:38,284
So that's 18 million for the first 40.

961
01:15:39,244 --> 01:15:42,288
Hell, TWA can't afford that.
The damn airline's flat broke.

962
01:15:46,460 --> 01:15:48,961
Guess I'll just have
to pay for them myself.

963
01:15:49,838 --> 01:15:52,923
Build them, Bob.
Send the bill to Noah Dietrich.

964
01:15:53,091 --> 01:15:54,633
Oh, and thank you.

965
01:15:58,388 --> 01:16:00,222
Merry Christmas.

966
01:16:00,390 --> 01:16:04,852
You've just placed the largest order for
airplanes in the history of the damn planet.

967
01:16:05,020 --> 01:16:07,146
Lockheed sent us a bill for $18 million.

968
01:16:07,314 --> 01:16:10,608
Don't get all hysterical on me, Noah.
It isn't good for you.

969
01:16:10,776 --> 01:16:14,111
- This is a lot of money for planes.
- I know it's a lot of money.

970
01:16:14,279 --> 01:16:17,907
It's too damn much. You think I've got
$18 million in petty cash?

971
01:16:18,075 --> 01:16:20,242
I should've told you. It slipped my mind.

972
01:16:20,410 --> 01:16:22,328
- Slipped your mind? Oh, for --
- Right.

973
01:16:22,496 --> 01:16:25,956
- I'll get back to you. Bye.
- How could $18 million slip your mind?

974
01:16:26,833 --> 01:16:30,002
Hey, honey.
What are you doing home?

975
01:16:34,424 --> 01:16:37,259
You're not one for tears, and, well ...

976
01:16:37,427 --> 01:16:41,680
... neither am l,
so it's best to come out with it.

977
01:16:44,810 --> 01:16:49,021
I've met someone.
I've fallen in love and I'm moving out.

978
01:16:51,650 --> 01:16:56,403
If I could make it
any more gentle, I would.

979
01:16:56,571 --> 01:17:00,658
But I can't, so ...

980
01:17:01,701 --> 01:17:03,577
... there we both are.

981
01:17:07,207 --> 01:17:09,041
Let's be honest.

982
01:17:09,209 --> 01:17:13,712
It's all been a grand adventure,
but it couldn't possibly last.

983
01:17:13,880 --> 01:17:16,757
We're too alike, you and I.

984
01:17:19,886 --> 01:17:21,220
You met someone?

985
01:17:21,388 --> 01:17:25,307
Someone more appropriate.
To me, I mean.

986
01:17:28,019 --> 01:17:30,980
What does that mean,
"more appropriate"?

987
01:17:31,398 --> 01:17:35,484
Someone more attuned to my needs.

988
01:17:36,027 --> 01:17:37,945
Look at me, Katie.

989
01:17:38,113 --> 01:17:40,030
Stop acting.

990
01:17:40,448 --> 01:17:43,242
I'm not acting.

991
01:17:47,873 --> 01:17:50,499
I wonder if you even know anymore.

992
01:17:55,422 --> 01:17:57,631
Don't be unkind.

993
01:18:00,343 --> 01:18:02,052
You ...?

994
01:18:03,388 --> 01:18:04,722
You wanna go?

995
01:18:08,351 --> 01:18:09,977
Go on.

996
01:18:10,562 --> 01:18:13,689
Actresses are cheap in this town, darling.

997
01:18:13,857 --> 01:18:16,442
- And I got a lot of money.
- This is beneath you.

998
01:18:16,610 --> 01:18:19,069
No, no, this is exactly me.

999
01:18:19,237 --> 01:18:24,366
You tell me you're leaving me, and you
have the nerve to expect graciousness?

1000
01:18:24,826 --> 01:18:26,827
I expect a little maturity.

1001
01:18:26,995 --> 01:18:29,914
I expect you to face the situation
like an adult who --

1002
01:18:30,081 --> 01:18:32,374
Don't talk down to me!

1003
01:18:32,542 --> 01:18:35,544
Don't you ever talk down to me!
You are a movie star.

1004
01:18:35,712 --> 01:18:37,296
Nothing more.

1005
01:19:49,327 --> 01:19:51,245
Don't answer it.

1006
01:19:54,124 --> 01:19:55,833
What is it, Howard?

1007
01:19:56,001 --> 01:19:58,294
Hey, Noah ...

1008
01:19:58,461 --> 01:20:01,463
... I need you to get to Penney's
and buy me some clothes.

1009
01:20:01,631 --> 01:20:03,424
- Penney's isn't open.
- Oh, shit.

1010
01:20:03,591 --> 01:20:06,552
- It's 2 in the morning.
- Yeah, that's right.

1011
01:20:06,720 --> 01:20:09,430
Well, first thing tomorrow, then, all right?

1012
01:20:09,597 --> 01:20:12,683
I need two new suits off the rack.
One light and one dark.

1013
01:20:12,851 --> 01:20:16,061
Three white shirts and three pairs
of white tennis shoes. Got that?

1014
01:20:16,229 --> 01:20:18,188
- Yeah.
- No, no.

1015
01:20:18,356 --> 01:20:20,190
- Make it Woolworth's.
- Woolworth's.

1016
01:20:20,358 --> 01:20:22,943
No, no, Penney's. Penney's.

1017
01:20:23,111 --> 01:20:24,862
All right.

1018
01:20:25,572 --> 01:20:28,365
I'll get into it as soon as I can, Howard.

1019
01:20:28,700 --> 01:20:31,243
- All right?
- Noah, do you have a recorder?

1020
01:20:31,953 --> 01:20:35,164
- No.
- Are you recording this conversation?

1021
01:20:35,332 --> 01:20:37,750
- No.
- Okay.

1022
01:20:37,917 --> 01:20:39,752
I trust you.

1023
01:20:40,754 --> 01:20:44,131
- Howard --
- I need those suits first thing tomorrow.

1024
01:20:44,299 --> 01:20:47,760
- All right.
- Wait. Did I say Penney's or Woolworth's?

1025
01:20:47,927 --> 01:20:50,596
- Penney's.
- Better make it Sears.

1026
01:20:50,764 --> 01:20:53,265
All right, then, Sears.

1027
01:20:56,102 --> 01:20:58,270
I'm sorry, honey.

1028
01:20:59,481 --> 01:21:01,774
If I don't answer, he'll just call back.

1029
01:21:23,630 --> 01:21:26,673
Stop there, if you please, Miss Domergue.

1030
01:21:32,555 --> 01:21:34,473
Have you had surgery, Miss Domergue?

1031
01:21:36,309 --> 01:21:37,810
No.

1032
01:21:38,645 --> 01:21:41,730
Do you have scars of any kind?

1033
01:21:43,149 --> 01:21:44,650
No.

1034
01:21:46,319 --> 01:21:48,445
Wipe off your lipstick.

1035
01:21:52,992 --> 01:21:54,284
That's much better.

1036
01:21:55,870 --> 01:22:00,791
Now, you understand that you'd be
under contract to me? Personally.

1037
01:22:01,709 --> 01:22:03,335
Do you know what that means?

1038
01:22:12,178 --> 01:22:13,971
Now turn around for me.

1039
01:22:22,230 --> 01:22:23,730
Very nice.

1040
01:22:24,858 --> 01:22:26,733
You move well.

1041
01:22:29,571 --> 01:22:31,530
You live with your family, do you?

1042
01:22:33,658 --> 01:22:35,242
Yes.

1043
01:22:35,702 --> 01:22:37,244
That's nice.

1044
01:22:38,580 --> 01:22:40,372
Tell me something.

1045
01:22:41,708 --> 01:22:44,126
How old are you, Miss Domergue?

1046
01:22:47,088 --> 01:22:48,881
Fifteen.

1047
01:22:52,260 --> 01:22:53,427
Holy Mother of God.

1048
01:23:12,864 --> 01:23:16,658
Well, a car picks me up
every morning at 8, and off I go.

1049
01:23:16,826 --> 01:23:19,870
I'm getting my high school diploma.

1050
01:23:20,038 --> 01:23:22,748
Howard thinks that education is important.

1051
01:23:22,916 --> 01:23:25,292
- That's right.
- And then, after classes ...

1052
01:23:25,460 --> 01:23:29,046
... I'm off for elocution
and grooming and fittings.

1053
01:23:29,214 --> 01:23:31,006
Well, blow me down.

1054
01:23:32,217 --> 01:23:34,426
Pan Am's working
out of the Cocoanut Grove?

1055
01:23:34,594 --> 01:23:36,553
- Hello, Jack.
- Hello, Juan.

1056
01:23:36,721 --> 01:23:38,430
Helen, good to see you.

1057
01:23:38,598 --> 01:23:41,099
- How are you, Howard?
- Good, thanks.

1058
01:23:41,267 --> 01:23:43,101
- This is Faith Domergue.
- Sit down.

1059
01:23:43,269 --> 01:23:45,103
- Pleasure.
- What are you doing here?

1060
01:23:45,271 --> 01:23:48,106
Well, I'm out to meet
with Douglas about the DC-4.

1061
01:23:48,274 --> 01:23:52,110
It's our new plane, and it is
gonna be a pip, let me tell you.

1062
01:23:52,278 --> 01:23:55,489
- How's the Constellation coming?
- Good.

1063
01:23:55,782 --> 01:23:57,074
Great.

1064
01:23:58,451 --> 01:24:00,953
So how about letting me steal a peek?

1065
01:24:02,956 --> 01:24:04,915
I don't think so.

1066
01:24:05,083 --> 01:24:08,126
I should be cross with you.
You stole Ray Loewy from us.

1067
01:24:08,920 --> 01:24:12,464
- He's doing our interior design. That's right.
- He was doing ours.

1068
01:24:14,968 --> 01:24:16,718
So ...

1069
01:24:17,262 --> 01:24:19,721
... what are your colors?
- Stop fishing.

1070
01:24:21,474 --> 01:24:23,976
So you have buttons ...

1071
01:24:24,143 --> 01:24:25,561
... or zippers?

1072
01:24:25,979 --> 01:24:27,271
I'm sorry?

1073
01:24:29,190 --> 01:24:33,110
Buttons or zippers for the drapes
on the sleeping berths?

1074
01:24:36,614 --> 01:24:38,282
Zippers.

1075
01:24:47,166 --> 01:24:48,750
Buttons.

1076
01:24:58,428 --> 01:25:01,430
So I suppose you'll be
expanding on down to Mexico.

1077
01:25:01,931 --> 01:25:05,475
- Why do you say that?
- Well, your range is 3000 miles.

1078
01:25:05,643 --> 01:25:09,730
I'd imagine you'd expand from Los Angeles
to Mexico and South America.

1079
01:25:09,897 --> 01:25:12,065
Hey, that's a good idea.
Anyone got a pen?

1080
01:25:12,233 --> 01:25:14,359
Or across the Atlantic.

1081
01:25:17,363 --> 01:25:19,281
You've had enough of this ice cream.

1082
01:25:19,449 --> 01:25:23,035
You give me that spoon. You don't
wanna get your gloves all sticky.

1083
01:25:24,996 --> 01:25:26,872
Isn't that too far?

1084
01:25:31,878 --> 01:25:33,795
New York ...

1085
01:25:33,963 --> 01:25:36,006
... to Newfoundland ...

1086
01:25:36,716 --> 01:25:37,966
... to Ireland.

1087
01:25:43,222 --> 01:25:44,806
To Paris.

1088
01:25:51,939 --> 01:25:53,565
Well ...

1089
01:25:54,108 --> 01:25:56,234
... Pan Am welcomes you.

1090
01:25:56,402 --> 01:25:58,236
We're overbooked as it is.

1091
01:25:58,404 --> 01:26:02,032
It's such a burden doing it all
on your own, let me tell you.

1092
01:26:02,200 --> 01:26:04,242
So when's the Connie gonna be ready?

1093
01:26:04,410 --> 01:26:07,079
- Next year maybe. DC-4?
- Next year.

1094
01:26:07,246 --> 01:26:10,415
Well, we look forward to her then.

1095
01:26:10,958 --> 01:26:12,709
And I to the Connie.

1096
01:26:14,587 --> 01:26:18,215
I've ordered the next 40 after you.

1097
01:26:18,424 --> 01:26:20,217
- It's Miss ...?
- Domergue.

1098
01:26:20,385 --> 01:26:23,762
Yes, of course. Now, was that a
rumba or a samba you were doing?

1099
01:26:24,180 --> 01:26:26,932
- I' was a samba.
- A samba, yes.

1100
01:26:27,100 --> 01:26:30,352
Howard, I never knew
you were such a good dancer.

1101
01:26:31,312 --> 01:26:33,146
Helen, Jack.

1102
01:26:34,982 --> 01:26:37,776
Good going. You gave away
our entire postwar strategy.

1103
01:26:37,944 --> 01:26:42,447
- He can't stop us.
- He's Pan Am. He can stop anything.

1104
01:26:44,450 --> 01:26:46,284
Give me the largest
Scotch you got.

1105
01:26:46,452 --> 01:26:50,038
I don't know what in the hell you're
so damn giddy about. Excuse me.

1106
01:28:42,109 --> 01:28:43,568
Jack.

1107
01:28:43,736 --> 01:28:47,364
Get in touch with Joyce and Berg.
Those are my boys in Washington.

1108
01:28:47,532 --> 01:28:50,909
Set up a meeting with Jones,
secretary of commerce, old golfing buddy.

1109
01:28:51,077 --> 01:28:54,037
- Slow down.
- We'll need terminals in Ireland and France.

1110
01:28:54,205 --> 01:28:55,664
I wanna get some tax breaks.

1111
01:28:55,832 --> 01:28:59,501
If that ass thinks he owns the world,
he's got another thing coming.

1112
01:28:59,669 --> 01:29:02,546
Pan Am owns Europe.
We ought to think about Mexico.

1113
01:29:02,713 --> 01:29:06,800
To hell with Mexico. No airline should
have a monopoly on flying the Atlantic.

1114
01:29:06,968 --> 01:29:10,262
It just isn't fair.
He owns Pan Am, he owns Congress.

1115
01:29:10,429 --> 01:29:14,266
He owns the Civil Aeronautics Board,
but he does not own the sky.

1116
01:29:14,433 --> 01:29:17,102
We're in a street fight
with that son of a bitch.

1117
01:29:17,270 --> 01:29:20,939
I've been fighting high-hat
Ivy League pricks like him my whole life.

1118
01:29:21,107 --> 01:29:24,734
And listen, fire Ray Loewy.
You goddamn heard me? Fire Ray Loewy.

1119
01:29:24,902 --> 01:29:28,280
He's spying for Trippe.
That shitheel knew all about the buttons.

1120
01:29:28,447 --> 01:29:30,448
Spies in my midst, Jack.

1121
01:29:31,117 --> 01:29:32,951
Spies in my midst.

1122
01:29:47,383 --> 01:29:50,302
- Hello, Howard.
- Roland.

1123
01:29:52,179 --> 01:29:53,763
So ...

1124
01:29:53,931 --> 01:29:55,473
... what can I do for you?

1125
01:29:58,644 --> 01:30:02,647
I want all the pictures you have
of Kate Hepburn and Spencer Tracy.

1126
01:30:02,815 --> 01:30:06,359
All the negatives.
And I want you to kill the story.

1127
01:30:06,527 --> 01:30:09,905
Howard, he's a married man.
He's a Catholic.

1128
01:30:10,072 --> 01:30:12,324
They're movie stars.
Fair game all around.

1129
01:30:20,833 --> 01:30:23,001
My office knows where I am, Howard.

1130
01:30:24,003 --> 01:30:26,838
I'm not gonna kill you, Roland.

1131
01:30:27,006 --> 01:30:28,924
I don't do that.

1132
01:30:33,679 --> 01:30:36,306
- How much?
- Not for sale.

1133
01:30:39,560 --> 01:30:41,144
How much?

1134
01:30:42,021 --> 01:30:45,190
Not for sale.

1135
01:30:48,527 --> 01:30:50,612
You ever cheat on your wife, Roland?

1136
01:30:52,406 --> 01:30:54,866
You ever screw a colored girl?

1137
01:30:55,534 --> 01:30:58,703
You ever steal anything?
You ever hurt anyone?

1138
01:31:00,873 --> 01:31:02,707
Good night, Howard.

1139
01:31:03,084 --> 01:31:06,044
You ever go to
a Communist Party meeting, Roland?

1140
01:31:15,888 --> 01:31:18,056
TWA stock.

1141
01:31:19,058 --> 01:31:20,350
How much?

1142
01:31:21,936 --> 01:31:23,395
Fifty thousand shares.

1143
01:31:24,063 --> 01:31:25,522
Ten.

1144
01:31:28,567 --> 01:31:29,901
All right.

1145
01:31:33,030 --> 01:31:34,864
This isn't gonna be that easy.

1146
01:31:35,241 --> 01:31:38,618
He's been making big contributions
on both sides of the aisle.

1147
01:31:38,786 --> 01:31:42,247
And Jack Frye is out there
lobbying everybody in town.

1148
01:31:42,415 --> 01:31:45,583
The French and British ambassadors
are lined up on his side.

1149
01:31:46,919 --> 01:31:50,088
I'm telling you, TWA is serious
about going international.

1150
01:31:50,256 --> 01:31:51,881
Okay.

1151
01:31:52,049 --> 01:31:53,967
Point, Mr. Hughes.

1152
01:31:54,343 --> 01:31:58,013
I think it's time for you to introduce
the community airline bill ...

1153
01:31:58,180 --> 01:31:59,723
... on the floor of the Senate.

1154
01:32:00,725 --> 01:32:03,518
- Is it done?
- My people are finishing it right now.

1155
01:32:03,686 --> 01:32:08,231
I also have to get you on the committee
investigating the national defense.

1156
01:32:10,651 --> 01:32:13,737
On the committee or chairman?

1157
01:32:14,071 --> 01:32:16,740
I could be much more effective
as chairman.

1158
01:32:16,907 --> 01:32:20,660
It's a great public platform.
You know, it generates a lot of press.

1159
01:32:20,828 --> 01:32:24,289
- Wasn't Truman chairman of that committee?
- Yeah, right.

1160
01:32:24,457 --> 01:32:26,875
He's vice president.
Look what he did with it.

1161
01:32:27,043 --> 01:32:29,127
No, I think ...

1162
01:32:29,795 --> 01:32:31,755
I think chairman.

1163
01:32:32,423 --> 01:32:33,840
What do you think?

1164
01:32:35,885 --> 01:32:38,470
- Chairman. That is interesting.
- Yeah.

1165
01:32:38,637 --> 01:32:42,140
Let me show you
these specs for the DC-4.

1166
01:32:42,391 --> 01:32:45,852
Ava, what do you think about
Trans World Airlines?

1167
01:32:46,020 --> 01:32:48,563
Transcontinental and Western
doesn't fit anymore.

1168
01:32:48,731 --> 01:32:51,608
We're international,
we need a name that reflects that.

1169
01:32:51,776 --> 01:32:54,486
Trans World is good. Kind of peppy.

1170
01:32:54,653 --> 01:32:57,155
TWA, right?

1171
01:32:57,323 --> 01:33:00,116
That way you don't need
to repaint any of the planes.

1172
01:33:00,284 --> 01:33:02,452
That's you. Always pinching pennies.

1173
01:33:03,621 --> 01:33:05,622
Hand me my wrap.

1174
01:33:19,637 --> 01:33:21,805
Knock it off.

1175
01:33:28,020 --> 01:33:30,522
I have something for you.

1176
01:33:31,774 --> 01:33:33,608
Stay here.

1177
01:33:39,073 --> 01:33:41,741
- What the hell is this?
- It's a present.

1178
01:33:41,909 --> 01:33:43,827
Go on, open it.

1179
01:33:44,995 --> 01:33:48,456
Oh, a box of trash.
You shouldn't have.

1180
01:33:48,624 --> 01:33:50,333
Keep looking, keep looking.

1181
01:33:55,172 --> 01:33:57,215
It's a Kashmiri sapphire.

1182
01:33:57,383 --> 01:34:00,552
I had my boys all over
the damn globe looking for this.

1183
01:34:00,719 --> 01:34:01,970
Why?

1184
01:34:02,138 --> 01:34:03,388
Because.

1185
01:34:03,556 --> 01:34:05,223
Look.

1186
01:34:05,391 --> 01:34:07,433
It matches your eyes.

1187
01:34:07,601 --> 01:34:09,978
I am not for sale.

1188
01:34:10,146 --> 01:34:12,230
For chrissakes, it's just a present.

1189
01:34:12,398 --> 01:34:15,567
You can't buy me, Howard,
so stop trying.

1190
01:34:15,734 --> 01:34:19,320
Don't buy me any more diamonds
or sapphires or any other damn thing.

1191
01:34:19,488 --> 01:34:21,906
You can buy me dinner.
How about that?

1192
01:34:22,658 --> 01:34:23,908
Jesus, Ava.

1193
01:34:24,952 --> 01:34:28,037
It's bad enough I have to endure
those gym shoes of yours.

1194
01:34:28,205 --> 01:34:31,875
But I get all dolled up and we go out
in this jalopy without a hood.

1195
01:34:33,294 --> 01:34:36,421
Ava, will you marry me?

1196
01:34:36,589 --> 01:34:39,299
- No, Howard.
- Well, why not, for heaven's sake?

1197
01:34:39,466 --> 01:34:42,051
In the first place, I don't love you.

1198
01:34:42,219 --> 01:34:44,596
In the second place, I'm still married.

1199
01:34:44,763 --> 01:34:49,434
Look, you got girls stashed all over town.
You got a damn harem just at the Bel-Air.

1200
01:34:49,602 --> 01:34:51,561
Marry one of your bungalow girls.

1201
01:34:51,729 --> 01:34:55,523
Those are employees. I won't marry
an employee. How would that look?

1202
01:35:03,699 --> 01:35:04,949
What is going on?

1203
01:35:08,287 --> 01:35:10,914
- Oh, my God!
- Goddamn it!

1204
01:35:12,541 --> 01:35:13,791
Faith!

1205
01:35:14,585 --> 01:35:16,502
- Faith, what the hell?
- Look out!

1206
01:35:16,670 --> 01:35:19,380
Goddamn, what the hell are you doing?

1207
01:35:22,551 --> 01:35:25,303
- Are you okay, lady?
- What are you doing with her?

1208
01:35:25,471 --> 01:35:28,139
We are going to dinner.
Now, get out of there.

1209
01:35:28,307 --> 01:35:30,308
Get that crazy bitch away from me!

1210
01:35:30,476 --> 01:35:32,101
Don't you love me anymore?

1211
01:35:32,269 --> 01:35:33,811
Course I love you, pork chop.

1212
01:35:33,979 --> 01:35:35,772
Ava, look over here. Howard.

1213
01:35:36,482 --> 01:35:37,774
Hey.

1214
01:35:41,195 --> 01:35:43,821
Juan Trippe is working
with Senator Brewster now.

1215
01:35:43,989 --> 01:35:48,326
They're after you. If the community
airline bill becomes law, we are finished.

1216
01:35:48,494 --> 01:35:50,620
Pan Am will have a monopoly
on international travel.

1217
01:35:50,788 --> 01:35:53,331
Well, how can they justify it?
It's un-American.

1218
01:35:53,499 --> 01:35:57,335
Brewster is saying that nationalized
foreign carriers, like Air France ...

1219
01:35:57,503 --> 01:36:00,505
... can offer lower rates because
they don't have to compete.

1220
01:36:00,673 --> 01:36:04,008
Let's get rid of competition
and have a nationalized airline ...

1221
01:36:04,176 --> 01:36:07,220
... and why don't we make it Pan Am?
- I'm not kowtowing to anyone.

1222
01:36:07,388 --> 01:36:09,681
- Howard, I need you up here.
- One sec, Odie.

1223
01:36:09,848 --> 01:36:12,350
Look, we are Trans World Airlines,
all right?

1224
01:36:12,518 --> 01:36:16,896
Get me something with a circle or a globe
or something round, for God's sake.

1225
01:36:17,064 --> 01:36:18,356
- Speak up.
- One cut.

1226
01:36:18,524 --> 01:36:22,694
I don't give a rat's ass. I'm not making
a cut. I'll release it without a seal.

1227
01:36:22,861 --> 01:36:24,529
We gotta go public with this.

1228
01:36:24,697 --> 01:36:26,572
I'm gonna talk to Hearst ...

1229
01:36:26,740 --> 01:36:29,909
... but we gotta get
some senators on our side.

1230
01:36:30,077 --> 01:36:32,495
- What do you want me to do?
- What Trippe does.

1231
01:36:32,663 --> 01:36:35,373
Offshore operations.
See who's up for re-election ...

1232
01:36:35,541 --> 01:36:38,167
... let's start making donations.
- Bribe senators?

1233
01:36:38,585 --> 01:36:41,254
I don't want them bribed.
I want it done legally.

1234
01:36:41,422 --> 01:36:44,757
I want them bought.
Put a team of investigators on Brewster.

1235
01:36:44,925 --> 01:36:47,260
I need to know everything
about that shitbag.

1236
01:36:47,428 --> 01:36:50,346
Where he goes, what he says
and who he screws.

1237
01:36:50,514 --> 01:36:52,515
- Get into it right now.
- You got it.

1238
01:37:00,149 --> 01:37:01,566
Just give me a second.

1239
01:37:03,902 --> 01:37:06,904
- All right, what do you need?
- Rudder and elevators.

1240
01:37:07,573 --> 01:37:09,657
No. These are fine.

1241
01:37:09,825 --> 01:37:13,911
Have Simon and Pete get back to me on the
assemblies. We need a secondary system.

1242
01:37:14,079 --> 01:37:15,580
Okay.

1243
01:37:16,415 --> 01:37:19,083
Listen, we need to take
another look at the wheel.

1244
01:37:19,251 --> 01:37:22,086
- Jesus. The damn wheel?
- Yeah.

1245
01:37:22,254 --> 01:37:23,755
It just doesn't feel right.

1246
01:37:23,922 --> 01:37:27,925
Christ almighty, you've seen 8000
goddamn wheels. Choose one, please.

1247
01:37:28,093 --> 01:37:29,927
- Just one of them.
- I know, I know.

1248
01:37:30,095 --> 01:37:32,430
- This one?
- I know, this one ...

1249
01:37:32,598 --> 01:37:36,434
This one's pretty close. Pretty close.

1250
01:38:12,471 --> 01:38:13,971
Odie.

1251
01:38:14,890 --> 01:38:17,433
That man sweeping up over there ...

1252
01:38:17,601 --> 01:38:20,645
... does he work for me?
I mean, have you seen him before?

1253
01:38:20,813 --> 01:38:23,398
Name's Nick, something like that.

1254
01:38:25,651 --> 01:38:27,402
Why's he looking at me?

1255
01:38:29,613 --> 01:38:31,030
I don't know.

1256
01:38:33,158 --> 01:38:36,285
Fire him. And make sure
they use damp brooms from now on.

1257
01:38:36,453 --> 01:38:39,831
Respiratory diseases are expensive,
and I don't want lawsuits.

1258
01:38:39,998 --> 01:38:42,875
But can we at least proceed
with the instrument panel?

1259
01:38:43,043 --> 01:38:45,503
- The tool shop's ready.
- I wanna see the blueprints.

1260
01:38:45,671 --> 01:38:48,631
Look, Howard, the deadline
is now completely unrealistic.

1261
01:38:48,799 --> 01:38:51,342
The war is gonna be over
by the time she's done.

1262
01:38:51,510 --> 01:38:55,680
I need you to help consult on vital decisions,
and you're off dealing with movies.

1263
01:38:55,848 --> 01:38:58,850
You got 1,000 workers waiting
for you to make a decision --

1264
01:38:59,017 --> 01:39:00,643
Hey, Odie!

1265
01:39:00,811 --> 01:39:02,812
Take it easy, all right.

1266
01:39:02,980 --> 01:39:07,024
You're under pressure, but it's gonna
do me no good if you crack up on me.

1267
01:39:07,693 --> 01:39:09,444
All right? Look ...

1268
01:39:09,611 --> 01:39:11,946
... take a couple of hours off, all right.

1269
01:39:12,114 --> 01:39:13,990
- You just relax a little.
- Okay.

1270
01:39:14,408 --> 01:39:16,451
- See your wife.
- Okay.

1271
01:39:16,869 --> 01:39:18,202
All right.

1272
01:39:19,079 --> 01:39:22,331
- Be sure to show me all the blueprints.
- All right.

1273
01:39:23,959 --> 01:39:28,671
Show me all the blueprints.

1274
01:39:28,839 --> 01:39:32,467
I'm serious, now.
Show me all the blueprints.

1275
01:39:34,052 --> 01:39:35,720
Show me all the blueprints.

1276
01:39:35,888 --> 01:39:38,764
- Howard.
- Show me all the blueprints.

1277
01:39:38,932 --> 01:39:44,854
Show me all the blueprints.

1278
01:39:45,022 --> 01:39:47,106
I wanna get this done right.

1279
01:39:47,900 --> 01:39:55,740
Show me all the blueprints.

1280
01:39:55,908 --> 01:39:57,825
- Howard.
- Show me all the blueprints.

1281
01:39:57,993 --> 01:40:01,662
Show me all the blueprints.
Show me all the blueprints ...

1282
01:40:28,649 --> 01:40:31,108
Quarantine.

1283
01:40:32,110 --> 01:40:33,819
Q ...

1284
01:40:33,987 --> 01:40:35,947
... U ...

1285
01:40:36,114 --> 01:40:38,366
... A ...

1286
01:40:38,992 --> 01:40:40,952
... R ...

1287
01:40:41,620 --> 01:40:43,579
... A ...

1288
01:40:43,747 --> 01:40:45,248
... N ...

1289
01:40:45,415 --> 01:40:47,625
... T ...

1290
01:40:48,001 --> 01:40:49,585
... I ...

1291
01:40:49,753 --> 01:40:51,254
... N ...

1292
01:40:56,176 --> 01:40:58,219
... E.

1293
01:41:01,139 --> 01:41:03,224
Quarantine.

1294
01:41:41,221 --> 01:41:44,307
General McEwan. Colonel Bertrang.
Thanks for coming down.

1295
01:41:44,474 --> 01:41:46,642
Odie, you reading me okay?

1296
01:41:46,810 --> 01:41:48,019
Yeah, you're A-Okay.

1297
01:41:53,692 --> 01:41:56,861
All right, flight controls are active.
She's all yours.

1298
01:42:05,787 --> 01:42:08,122
Spotless.
No wiggle on the wheel or throttle.

1299
01:42:08,290 --> 01:42:10,124
Take it easy.

1300
01:42:27,142 --> 01:42:30,728
- How does she sound, Howard?
- She's whispering to me, buddy.

1301
01:42:30,896 --> 01:42:32,813
All right, make her sing.

1302
01:42:53,710 --> 01:42:56,921
Well, Odie, she can fly. Congratulations.

1303
01:42:57,089 --> 01:43:00,591
I'm glad to hear it. Retract landing gear
and climb to 5000 feet ...

1304
01:43:00,759 --> 01:43:02,343
... on a heading of 2-7-0.

1305
01:43:02,511 --> 01:43:08,391
Retracting landing gear and climbing
to 5,000 feet on a heading 2-7-0.

1306
01:43:12,896 --> 01:43:15,106
- She's fast.
- What's your air speed?

1307
01:43:15,273 --> 01:43:16,899
292.

1308
01:43:17,109 --> 01:43:20,611
- All right, take her back to 200.
- No damn way.

1309
01:43:46,430 --> 01:43:48,139
We gotta bring her home.

1310
01:43:48,306 --> 01:43:50,766
Scheduled time of one hour
and 45 minutes has elapsed.

1311
01:43:50,976 --> 01:43:53,894
- Set course for 0-9-0 --
- Ten more minutes. Roger that.

1312
01:43:54,062 --> 01:43:56,647
Negative, Howard. Bring her home.

1313
01:43:56,815 --> 01:44:02,695
Okay. Okay. Setting course for 0-9-0.

1314
01:44:03,405 --> 01:44:05,322
Preparing to descend.

1315
01:44:08,952 --> 01:44:12,204
- Jesus.
- What is it, Howard?

1316
01:44:13,498 --> 01:44:17,001
The right wing just dipped.
I'm losing starboard engine.

1317
01:44:17,461 --> 01:44:20,087
Increasing power to 2800 rpm.

1318
01:44:20,547 --> 01:44:21,797
Cutting back.

1319
01:44:22,174 --> 01:44:24,091
Increasing starboard engine only.

1320
01:44:25,218 --> 01:44:27,970
Cutting back. I'm losing altitude.

1321
01:44:28,138 --> 01:44:30,681
Check starboard-engine manifold pressure.

1322
01:44:31,558 --> 01:44:35,436
- It's good, but rpm's are low.
- Are both starboard props turning?

1323
01:44:35,604 --> 01:44:37,062
Hold on.

1324
01:44:37,314 --> 01:44:40,357
They are, but she's pulling me
back and starboard, Odie.

1325
01:44:40,525 --> 01:44:43,110
- How bad is your cross control?
- I'm at full left rudder ...

1326
01:44:43,278 --> 01:44:46,572
... and full left aileron,
but she won't stay level. Goddamn it.

1327
01:44:46,865 --> 01:44:49,700
- Give us your position.
- Two thousand feet over --

1328
01:44:49,868 --> 01:44:53,954
Oh, Christ, I don't know, Beverly Hills.
Fifteen hundred feet.

1329
01:44:54,122 --> 01:44:55,831
We're going down.

1330
01:44:56,750 --> 01:45:00,377
I'll try for the Wilshire Country Club.
Ninth hole. You reading me?

1331
01:45:00,545 --> 01:45:04,465
Wilshire Country Club, copy that.
Howard, reduce engines to 1,000.

1332
01:45:05,175 --> 01:45:10,137
I'm going down!
I'm not gonna make it, buddy!

1333
01:45:16,603 --> 01:45:18,395
Goddamn it!

1334
01:47:20,769 --> 01:47:24,271
Is there anyone else inside?
Is there anyone else?!

1335
01:47:24,439 --> 01:47:26,148
No.

1336
01:47:29,986 --> 01:47:33,364
I'm Howard Hughes, the aviator.

1337
01:47:42,624 --> 01:47:45,334
-- every inch of his
wiring and fluid connection.

1338
01:47:45,502 --> 01:47:48,170
He has burns to 78 percent of his body.

1339
01:47:48,338 --> 01:47:51,006
Nine ribs are shattered,
not broken, shattered ...

1340
01:47:51,508 --> 01:47:55,970
... as are his nose, his chin, his cheek,
his left knee, his left elbow.

1341
01:47:56,137 --> 01:47:58,722
He has 60 lacerations
on his face, to the bone.

1342
01:47:59,307 --> 01:48:02,059
His chest was crushed,
so his left lung collapsed ...

1343
01:48:02,227 --> 01:48:05,896
... and his heart has shifted
to the right side of his chest cavity.

1344
01:48:06,856 --> 01:48:08,732
Jesus, God.

1345
01:48:09,192 --> 01:48:13,529
- He's getting blood transfusions now, but --
- Whose blood?

1346
01:48:14,364 --> 01:48:16,532
- I'm sorry?
- Whose blood?

1347
01:48:17,033 --> 01:48:18,575
From our stock.

1348
01:48:19,244 --> 01:48:23,414
- Oh, he's not going to like that.
- Mr. Dietrich, I doubt he's ...

1349
01:48:23,581 --> 01:48:26,542
... ever gonna like or
dislike anything again.

1350
01:48:27,168 --> 01:48:29,336
I'm terribly sorry.

1351
01:48:57,782 --> 01:48:59,700
Orange juice.

1352
01:49:02,787 --> 01:49:06,248
It's not fresh from the kitchen, so I ...

1353
01:49:06,958 --> 01:49:12,046
I have them make it here so ...
So I can see.

1354
01:49:16,134 --> 01:49:18,093
Look at me.

1355
01:49:20,722 --> 01:49:22,723
I'm a monster.

1356
01:49:23,183 --> 01:49:27,978
Yeah. Orange juice has nutritional value.

1357
01:49:29,147 --> 01:49:34,151
There's ... There's some flies
outside my window, though.

1358
01:49:34,694 --> 01:49:36,487
So ...

1359
01:49:38,490 --> 01:49:41,158
... little Howard likes ...

1360
01:49:42,660 --> 01:49:44,787
... citrus.

1361
01:49:45,538 --> 01:49:47,414
Don't he just ...?

1362
01:49:50,543 --> 01:49:52,252
Tell me.

1363
01:49:53,880 --> 01:49:57,674
An oil seal ripped off
the starboard rear propeller.

1364
01:49:57,842 --> 01:50:01,345
When the pressure dropped,
the prop reversed pitch.

1365
01:50:01,846 --> 01:50:03,597
Do you understand me?

1366
01:50:04,140 --> 01:50:09,144
Howard, I'm sorry to have to tell you
this now, but there's something else.

1367
01:50:09,521 --> 01:50:12,272
- You following me?
- Yeah.

1368
01:50:13,483 --> 01:50:17,152
The Air Force canceled the contract
on The Hercules.

1369
01:50:19,489 --> 01:50:24,868
The war's over now,
and they say they don't need it anymore.

1370
01:50:25,370 --> 01:50:29,832
I have to know what you want me to do.
Should I release the staff?

1371
01:50:29,999 --> 01:50:32,084
How far ...

1372
01:50:33,878 --> 01:50:35,337
... from finishing?

1373
01:50:36,548 --> 01:50:41,385
- About six months.
- No, in money.

1374
01:50:44,639 --> 01:50:46,515
Seven million.

1375
01:50:47,308 --> 01:50:48,684
Maybe more.

1376
01:50:54,065 --> 01:50:55,899
Build it.

1377
01:50:57,402 --> 01:50:59,361
Build it, Odie.

1378
01:51:01,197 --> 01:51:02,739
Howard ...

1379
01:51:03,366 --> 01:51:07,411
... a Constellation crashed
outside Reading, Pennsylvania.

1380
01:51:07,912 --> 01:51:11,331
The Civil Aeronautics Board
has grounded the whole fleet.

1381
01:51:21,301 --> 01:51:22,968
You know ...

1382
01:51:24,053 --> 01:51:27,306
... Juan Trippe sent me flowers.

1383
01:51:29,517 --> 01:51:31,226
Take a look.

1384
01:51:34,981 --> 01:51:39,860
- What did you do with all the others?
- Oh, I had them taken out.

1385
01:51:40,028 --> 01:51:43,197
They ... They attract aphids.

1386
01:51:44,240 --> 01:51:48,952
Aphids are ...
They're just awful little creatures.

1387
01:51:49,787 --> 01:51:51,580
But ...

1388
01:51:53,917 --> 01:51:56,001
But these ones ...

1389
01:51:56,961 --> 01:52:00,839
... I wanted to see these ones every day.

1390
01:52:08,389 --> 01:52:11,391
Can white elephants fly?
That's everybody's question.

1391
01:52:11,559 --> 01:52:16,605
The hull of the world's mightiest airplane,
a flying boat built by Howard Hughes.

1392
01:52:16,773 --> 01:52:20,943
Two hundred and twenty feet long,
it towers higher than a five-story building.

1393
01:52:21,110 --> 01:52:25,113
Power lines have to be cut as it starts
the trip from Culver City ...

1394
01:52:25,281 --> 01:52:27,324
... to the Pacific, 30 miles away.

1395
01:52:27,492 --> 01:52:30,702
Moving the 60-ton load
is quite an engineering problem.

1396
01:52:30,870 --> 01:52:34,831
But you gotta ask, was anything this big
ever supposed to fly?

1397
01:52:34,999 --> 01:52:39,503
There goes one wing section,
160 feet long with four engine housings.

1398
01:52:39,671 --> 01:52:42,547
Double that and you've got some idea
of the wingspread.

1399
01:52:42,715 --> 01:52:47,010
An airplane that challenges
a mountain for sheer size.

1400
01:52:54,018 --> 01:52:56,270
How long can they keep us grounded?

1401
01:52:56,437 --> 01:53:00,023
Until they finish investigating
the Reading crash. Could be months.

1402
01:53:00,191 --> 01:53:05,112
You're running a $14 million deficit. How
will you afford to keep them out of service?

1403
01:53:05,321 --> 01:53:09,825
- We go international, we'll make it up.
- Brewster's C.A.B. bill isn't going away.

1404
01:53:09,993 --> 01:53:12,703
That bill passes,
and you bought these for nothing.

1405
01:53:12,870 --> 01:53:16,290
- We're fighting the C.A.B. bill.
- Meanwhile, how do we keep TWA flying?

1406
01:53:16,457 --> 01:53:21,044
Don't say, "Just go to Tool Co." We're
pumping every cent into The Hercules ...

1407
01:53:21,212 --> 01:53:24,047
... which the Air Force
doesn't even want anymore.

1408
01:53:24,215 --> 01:53:27,968
I'm glad Jack is feeling sunny about things,
but I've seen the books.

1409
01:53:28,303 --> 01:53:30,721
I'm telling it straight. I'm not crying wolf.

1410
01:53:30,888 --> 01:53:34,016
We're in serious trouble.
You've gotta make a choice.

1411
01:53:34,183 --> 01:53:39,229
You wanna be bankrupted
by the big plane or by the big airline?

1412
01:53:46,571 --> 01:53:50,157
Go see Thomas Parkinson
at the Equitable in New York.

1413
01:53:50,325 --> 01:53:53,910
Get a loan against
all the TWA equipment and capital.

1414
01:53:54,078 --> 01:53:59,916
Use the planes as collateral. Hell, use the
desks, use the pens, use everything we got.

1415
01:54:00,084 --> 01:54:04,254
- Try to get me 40 million.
- And if TWA defaults on the loan?

1416
01:54:04,839 --> 01:54:07,758
Then Juan Trippe buys us cheap.

1417
01:54:10,345 --> 01:54:13,430
Under my bed! You put a goddamn
microphone under my bed!

1418
01:54:13,598 --> 01:54:15,766
Listen to me.
I am concerned about you.

1419
01:54:15,933 --> 01:54:19,269
- I just wanna make sure you're okay.
- And who is in that car?!

